# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arkive
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arkive/arkive] The project was an initiative of Wildscreen, a UK-registered educational charity, based in Bristol.
[src:arkive/arkive] The technical platform was created by Hewlett-Packard, as part of the HP Labs' Digital Media Systems research programme.
[src:arkive/arkive] It was a member of the Institutional Council of the Encyclopedia of Life.
[src:arkive/arkive] Two ARKive layers for Google Earth, featuring endangered species and species in the Gulf of Mexico were produced by Google Earth Outreach.
[src:arkive/arkive] The first of these was launched in April 2008 by Wildscreen's Patron, Sir David Attenborough.
[src:arkive/arkive] Due to lack of funding, the website was closed on 15 February 2019 and the media collection taken offline.
[src:arkive/arkive] Its successor, Wildscreen ARK (https://wildscreenark.org/), was launched in February 2024.
[src:arkive/arkive] The project formally was launched on 20 May 2003 by its patron, the UK-based natural history presenter, Sir David Attenborough, a long-standing colleague and friend of its chief instigator, the late Christopher Parsons, a former Head of the BBC Natural History Unit.
[src:arkive/arkive] Parsons never lived to see the fruition of the project, succumbing to cancer in November 2002 at the age of 70.
[src:arkive/arkive] Parsons identified a need to provide a centralised safe haven for wildlife films and photographs after discovering that many such records are held in scattered, non-indexed, collections, often with little or no public access, and sometimes in conditions that could lead to loss or damage.
[src:arkive/arkive] He believed the records could be a powerful force in building environmental awareness by bringing scientific names to life.
[src:arkive/arkive] He also saw their preservation as an important educational resource and conservation tool, not at least because extinction rates and habitat destruction could mean that images and sounds might be the only legacy of some species' existence.
[src:arkive/arkive] Media was digitised to the highest available quality without compression and encoded to open standards.
[src:arkive/arkive] A prototype site was online as early as April 1999.
[src:arkive/arkive] There were several design iterations before the formal launch.
[src:arkive/arkive] By the launch date, the project team had researched, catalogued, copied, described and authenticated image, sound and fact files of 1,000 animals, plants and fungi, many of them critically endangered.
[src:arkive/arkive] More multi-media profiles are added every month, starting with British flora and fauna and with species included on the Red List – that is, species that are believed to be closest to extinction, according to research by the World Conservation Union.
[src:arkive/arkive] By January 2006, the database had grown to 2,000 species, 15,000 still images and more than 50 hours of videos.
[src:arkive/arkive] By 2010, over 5,500 donors had contributed 70,000 film clips and photos of more than 12,000 species.
[src:arkive/arkive] In February 2019, Wildscreen announced that they "...have had to make the very hard decision to close the Arkive website on 15 February 2019", due to funding issues.
[src:arkive/arkive] The site was *Sunday Times* website of the year for 2005.
[src:arkive/arkive] It was a 2010 Webby Award honouree for its outstanding calibre of work, in the 'Education' category, and a 2010 Association of Educational Publishers 'Distinguished Achievement Award' winner, in the category for websites for 9-to-12-year-olds.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] The **BBC Studios Natural History Unit** (**NHU**) is a department of BBC Studios that produces television, radio and online content with a natural history or wildlife theme.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] It is best known for its highly regarded nature documentaries, including *The Blue Planet* and *Planet Earth*, and has a long association with David Attenborough's authored documentaries, starting with 1979's *Life on Earth*.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] The Natural History Unit is a specialist department within BBC Studios Productions.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Each year it produces around 100 hours of television and 50 hours of radio programmes, making it the largest wildlife documentary production house in the world.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] The BBC commissions programmes from the Unit for broadcast on five terrestrial television channels (BBC One, BBC Two, BBC Four, CBBC and CBeebies) and BBC Radio 4.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] It also makes programmes for other broadcasters and services including Apple TV+, Warner Bros.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Discovery, National Geographic Global Networks and NBC Universal.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Content is marketed internationally under the BBC Earth brand.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Original content is also broadcast on the *Earth Unplugged* YouTube channel.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] The Unit was based in Broadcasting House, Bristol since its formation in 1957 until 2022, in 2022 it moved to Bridgewater House, along with BBC Studios Factual Entertainment Productions.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] It has been headed by Jonny Keeling since 2021.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] The BBC natural history unit's links to Bristol date back to the 1940s, when Desmond Hawkins, then a young producer, joined the West Region staff.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] His personal interest in the subject led to a radio series called *The Naturalist*, which began on the Home Service in 1946 and proved an immediate success, later augmented by *Out of Doors* and *Birds in Britain*.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] By the early 1950s, Hawkins had been promoted to Head of Programmes, West Region and was keen to translate his success to the developing medium of television.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] At the time, radio still commanded much higher audiences than the fledgling television service, but Hawkins was not alone in recognising the potential for natural history programmes for the newer medium.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] His vision was shared by Frank Gillard, the regional Head, and the two men would become the driving force behind the establishment of the Natural History Unit (NHU) in Bristol.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Until such formalities were completed, natural history programmes were the responsibility of the Features office of the West Region.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] One of the first programmes was an outside broadcast from the Wildfowl and Wetlands Trust's centre at Slimbridge in 1953, the first TV collaboration between the BBC and Peter Scott.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Occasional programmes continued the following year, but it was not until 1955 that the BBC began a regular studio-based series, *Look*, presented by Scott.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] One of the early problems for the Unit was the difficulty in sourcing film stock.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] At the time, the only wildlife cameramen were amateurs, and the footage wasn't always good enough for broadcast.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] The embryo unit's first film camera, a clockwork Bolex, was bought from a Bristol camera shop with petty cash by Desmond's assistant, Tony Soper.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Some of Scott's own expedition films were used for early episodes of *Look*.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] One particularly outstanding film from 1955, shot by Heinz Sielmann, showed woodpeckers inside a nest hole.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] By 1957, with *Look* firmly established and Gillard and Hawkins lobbying hard, the BBC management in London approved the official formation of a Natural History Unit.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Gillard was on the search for a senior producer to head the new Unit, and asked David Attenborough to take on the role.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Attenborough had good credentials (he was a trained zoologist) but declined, having recently settled in London with his young family.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Instead, he was placed in charge of the newly formed **Travel and Exploration Unit**, striking a deal which would allow him to continue to film his popular *Zoo Quest* (1954–1963) series alongside natural history output from the fledgling Bristol unit.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] The Travel and Exploration Unit in London also introduced viewers to more exotic wildlife, and made household names of the first natural history presenters.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Armand and Michaela Denis filmed East African wildlife for their *On Safari* programmes, whilst another pioneering husband-and-wife team, Hans and Lotte Hass, created some of the first underwater films.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Nicholas Crocker, a senior producer with West Region, became the Unit's first Head in September 1957.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Founder members included Tony Soper (producer) and Christopher Parsons (assistant film editor), both of whom would go on to play a major part in the Unit's development.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Although much of the Unit's early output concentrated on British and European wildlife, one of its first productions to be broadcast was *Faraway Look* featuring Peter Scott in Australia.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] The early programmes were limited by the available technology, but it was also a time of great experimentation in style and content, bringing the Unit notable success.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] *Animal Magic* (1962–1983), presented by Johnny Morris and Tony Soper, was a successful format for young audiences which ran for over 20 years.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] The Unit also collaborated with Gerald Durrell on several films of his animal-collecting expeditions, beginning with the studio-based series *To Bafut for Beef* (April 1958), using African footage shot by Durrell.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] In the early 1960s, natural history filmmaking was being held back by the limitations of the available technology, particularly the restrictions of shooting often fast-moving subjects in poor light and spectacularly colourful subjects in black and white.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] The second of these problems was about to be resolved.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Around the same time, the technology to broadcast and receive colour television was being developed, and the BBC made funds available to begin filming in colour to allow filmmakers to experiment with the latest equipment in preparation for the switchover.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] *The Major* (1963), produced by Parsons and filmed largely by New Forest cameraman Eric Ashby, told the story of an ancient English oak and was the Unit's first colour production.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] This was one of six films made for the BBC by part-time film-makers Ron Peggs and Leslie Jackman.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Leslie filmed the insect sequences at his home in Paignton using specimens collected by John Burton.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Colour transmission finally arrived in 1967 on BBC 2 under the stewardship of David Attenborough, who had retired from programme-making to move into BBC administration.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] The first natural history film to be shown in colour was Ron Eastman's *The Private Life of the Kingfisher* (1968), written and produced by Jeffery Boswall.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Attenborough, by then controller of BBC 2, wanted to make a strong statement on BBC's second channel of the boundless possibilities that colour television offered, and recognised that natural history was the obvious subject matter to choose.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] He commissioned a series called *The World About Us* (1969–1982) that would broadcast in a 50-minute Sunday evening slot.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Because of the challenge of producing enough colour material, the commission was shared between the NHU and London's Travel and Exploration Unit.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] The extended opportunities offered by the 50-minute format and improvements in film technology and expertise finally allowed the NHU to begin showcasing its talent.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] One of Attenborough's main achievements as Controller of BBC 2 was to commission *Civilisation* (1969), a major series presented by the respected art historian Kenneth Clark.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] It was a resounding success with critics and the public, pioneering the 'personal view' form of documentary films for television.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Parsons, by then an experienced producer with the NHU, recognised the potential for a similar treatment with natural history as the subject and approached Attenborough in 1970 with the idea.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Attenborough was receptive, even to the idea that he should present the series, but both men realised at that time that it was beyond the scope of the Unit's capabilities.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] When Attenborough resigned from his administrative duties to return to programme making at the start of 1973, planning for the proposed series resumed.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] It was another three years before the resourcing and financing were agreed, the outline episode scripts written (by Attenborough) and a production team in place.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Parsons would serve as series producer and share production duties for the individual episodes with Richard Brock and John Sparks.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Filming took place in 39 countries, featured over 650 different species and involved over 1 million miles of travel.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Attenborough himself has said that if it had not been for computerised airline schedules, the series would have probably been impossible to undertake.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] When it was finally broadcast in 1979 on BBC 1, *Life on Earth* drew an audience of 15 million people in the UK and was eventually seen by an estimated 500 million people worldwide.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] The Natural History Unit made its name with *Life on Earth*, and was rewarded by being awarded departmental status by BBC management in December 1979.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Christopher Parsons, by then its most experienced producer, became the first official Head of the Unit.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] It celebrated its silver jubilee in 1982 with the miniseries *Flight of the Condor*, and sealed its reputation as one of the foremost production companies for popular natural history films in the following decades.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] A succession of series have followed the format established by *Life on Earth*, often presented or narrated by Attenborough, and transmitted on the BBC's main channel.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] *The Blue Planet* (2001) and *Planet Earth* (2006) typify these signature programmes, characterised by high production values, specially-commissioned musical scores and often ground-breaking footage of wildlife from around the globe.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] The NHU has also diversified into other programme formats.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Its *Diary* series have featured African big cats, elephants, orang-utans and bears in a nightly wildlife soap opera.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Among of the longest-running programmes has been *Wildlife on One* (1977–2005) which was broadcast in a regular evening slot.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] The *Continents* strand on BBC Two has featured series on all the world's major land areas over the past eighteen years, including *Spirits of the Jaguar* (1996), *Land of the Tiger* (1997), *Andes to Amazon* (2000) and *Wild Down Under* (2003).
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Also on BBC Two, the annual *Springwatch* (since 2005) and *Autumnwatch* (since 2006) series have brought live pictures of British wildlife into millions of homes.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] In 2007, the Unit celebrated its 50th anniversary and was rewarded with a special award at the International Broadcasting Convention in recognition of its unique contribution to wildlife film and documentary making.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] On television, the anniversary was marked with the broadcast of *Saving Planet Earth*, a conservation-themed series which helped to raise over £1.5 million for the BBC Wildlife Fund.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] In October 2007, the BBC announced that the NHU would suffer cuts of a third in both staff numbers and its £37 million annual budget, as a result of the Government's decision to impose a lower than inflation increase in the television licence fee.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] The cutbacks were widely condemned within the media industry and by programme-makers, including David Attenborough.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] In response to the criticism, Keith Scholey, Factual Controller of BBC Vision, promised that the BBC would "continue to make and show the ambitious, large-scale, truly memorable series that audiences associate with BBC natural history output".
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Titles affected by the cuts include the BBC Two *Wild* strand.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Productions already underway were not affected by the cuts, so the following year came *Wild China*, *Pacific Abyss*, *Lost Land of the Jaguar* and *Big Cat Live*, as well as the Unit's most ambitious radio event to date, *World on the Move*.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] *Natural World* also received a three-year commission from BBC Two on its 25th anniversary.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Post 2010, a greater emphasis was placed on climate change, which several special programmes broadcast focusing on the issue.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] More broadly, series looked at the negative effects of climate change and habitat destruction within series that did not focus solely on the topic.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] In 2016, BBC's non-news content production, including natural history, was separated into a commercial subsidiary BBC Studios.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] NHU head Wendy Darke departed and was succeeded by Julian Hector.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Since its inception in the 1950s, the Natural History Unit has produced a wealth of material for television, radio, and more recently, cinema.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Being the first and the largest production unit devoted to natural history programme making, it maintains an extensive archive of images and sound recordings as well as film materials.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] The filmography article presents a chronological summary of the Unit's major television and film productions.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] The Natural History Unit as a whole was awarded the Gold Medal at the 2001 Royal Television Society awards for its "outstanding contribution over the past 44 years to broadcasting about the natural world".
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] It was praised for being "a national resource for people's understanding and love of wildlife on our planet, and a symbol of both quality and talent in public service broadcasting".
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Recognition has also come in the form of high audience viewing figures and audience approval ratings, particularly for 'blue-chip' series such as *Planet Earth*.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] When first screened in the UK it was watched by more than 8 million people.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] In 2008, episodes of *Life in Cold Blood* and the *Wildlife Special* miniseries *Tiger: Spy in the Jungle* both reportedly achieved the highest-ever audience appreciation index (AI) rating for a factual programme.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Content is marketed internationally under BBC Studios' BBC Earth brand.
[src:arkive/bbc-natural-history-unit] Original content is also broadcast on the BBC Earth YouTube channel.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In 2019, it was reported in an Ofcom report that the BBC spent £136m on news during the period April 2018 to March 2019.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC News' domestic, global and online news divisions are housed within the largest live newsroom in Europe, in Broadcasting House in central London.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Parliamentary coverage is produced and broadcast from studios in London.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Through BBC English Regions, the BBC also has regional centres across England and national news centres in Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] All nations and English regions produce their own local news programmes and other current affairs and sport programmes.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The BBC is a quasi-autonomous corporation authorised by royal charter, making it operationally independent of the government.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] As of 2024, the BBC reaches an average of 450 million people per week, with the BBC World Service accounting for 320 million people.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The British Broadcasting Company broadcast its first radio bulletin from radio station 2LO on 14 November 1922.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Wishing to avoid competition, newspaper publishers persuaded the government to ban the BBC from broadcasting news before 7 pm, and to force it to use wire service copy instead of reporting on its own.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The BBC gradually gained the right to edit the copy and, in 1934, created its own news operation.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] However, it could not broadcast news before 6 p.m. until World War II.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In addition to news, Gaumont British and Movietone cinema newsreels had been broadcast on the TV service since 1936, with the BBC producing its own equivalent *Television Newsreel* programme from January 1948.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] A weekly *Children's Newsreel* was inaugurated on 23 April 1950, to around 350,000 receivers.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The network began simulcasting its radio news on television in 1946, with a still picture of Big Ben.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Televised bulletins began on 5 July 1954, broadcast from leased studios within Alexandra Palace in London.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The public's interest in television and live events was stimulated by Elizabeth II's coronation in 1953.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] It is estimated that up to 27 million people viewed the programme in the UK, overtaking radio's audience of 12 million for the first time.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Those live pictures were fed from 21 cameras in central London to Alexandra Palace for transmission, and then on to other UK transmitters opened in time for the event.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] That year, there were around two million TV Licences held in the UK, rising to over three million the following year, and four and a half million by 1955.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Television news, although physically separate from its radio counterpart, was still firmly under radio news' control in the 1950s.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Correspondents provided reports for both outlets, and the first televised bulletin, shown on 5 July 1954 on the then BBC television service and presented by Richard Baker, involved his providing narration off-screen while stills were shown.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] This was then followed by the customary *Television Newsreel* with a recorded commentary by John Snagge (and on other occasions by Andrew Timothy).
[src:arkive/bbc-news] On-screen newsreaders were introduced a year later in 1955 – Kenneth Kendall (the first to appear in vision), Robert Dougall, and Richard Baker—three weeks before ITN's launch on 21 September 1955.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Mainstream television production had started to move out of Alexandra Palace in 1950 to larger premises – mainly at Lime Grove Studios in Shepherd's Bush, west London – taking Current Affairs (then known as Talks Department) with it.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] It was from here that the first *Panorama*, a new documentary programme, was transmitted on 11 November 1953, with Richard Dimbleby becoming anchor in 1955.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In 1958, Hugh Carleton Greene became head of News and Current Affairs.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] On 1 January 1960, Greene became Director-General.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Greene made changes that were aimed at making BBC reporting more similar to its competitor ITN, which had been highly rated by study groups held by Greene.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] A newsroom was created at Alexandra Palace, television reporters were recruited and given the opportunity to write and voice their own scripts, without having to cover stories for radio too.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] On 20 June 1960, Nan Winton, the first female BBC network newsreader, appeared in vision.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] 19 September 1960 saw the start of the radio news and current affairs programme *The Ten O'clock News*.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC2 started transmission on 20 April 1964 and began broadcasting a new show, *Newsroom*.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] On Sunday 17 September 1967, *The World This Weekend*, a weekly news and current affairs programme, launched on what was then Home Service, but soon-to-be Radio 4.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Preparations for colour began in the autumn of 1967 and on Thursday 7 March 1968 *Newsroom* on BBC2 moved to an early evening slot, becoming the first UK news programme to be transmitted in colour – from Studio A at Alexandra Palace.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] *News Review* and *Westminster* (the latter a weekly review of Parliamentary happenings) were "colourised" shortly after.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] However, much of the insert material was still in black and white, as initially only a part of the film coverage shot in and around London was on colour reversal film stock, and all regional and many international contributions were still in black and white.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Colour facilities at Alexandra Palace were technically very limited for the next eighteen months, as it had only one RCA colour Quadruplex videotape machine and, eventually two Pye plumbicon colour telecines–although the news colour service started with just one.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] *Town and Around* was never to make the move to Television Centre – instead it became *London This Week* which aired on Mondays and Fridays only, from the new TVC studios.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The BBC moved production out of Alexandra Palace in 1969.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC Television News resumed operations the next day with a lunchtime bulletin on BBC1 – in black and white – from Television Centre, where it remained until March 2013.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] This move to a smaller studio with better technical facilities allowed *Newsroom* and *News Review* to replace back projection with colour-separation overlay.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] During the 1960s, satellite communication had become possible; however, it was some years before digital line-store conversion was able to undertake the process seamlessly.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] On 14 September 1970, the first *Nine O'Clock News* was broadcast on television.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Robert Dougall presented the first week from studio N1 – described by *The Guardian* as "a sort of polystyrene padded cell"—the bulletin having been moved from the earlier time of 20.50 as a response to the ratings achieved by ITN's *News at Ten*, introduced three years earlier on the rival ITV.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Richard Baker and Kenneth Kendall presented subsequent weeks, thus echoing those first television bulletins of the mid-1950s.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Angela Rippon became the first female news presenter of the *Nine O'Clock News* in 1975.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Her work outside the news was controversial at the time, appearing on *The Morecambe and Wise Christmas Show* in 1976 singing and dancing.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The first edition of *John Craven's Newsround*, initially intended only as a short series and later renamed just *Newsround*, came from studio N3 on 4 April 1972.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Afternoon television news bulletins during the mid to late 1970s were broadcast from the BBC newsroom itself, rather than one of the three news studios.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The newsreader would present to camera while sitting on the edge of a desk; behind him staff would be seen working busily at their desks.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] This period corresponded with when the *Nine O'Clock News* got its next makeover, and would use a CSO background of the newsroom from that very same camera each weekday evening.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Also in the mid-1970s, the late night news on BBC2 was briefly renamed *Newsnight*, but this was not to last, or be the same programme as we know today – that would be launched in 1980 – and it soon reverted to being just a news summary with the early evening BBC2 news expanded to become *Newsday*.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] News on radio was to change in the 1970s, and on Radio 4 in particular, brought about by the arrival of new editor Peter Woon from television news and the implementation of the *Broadcasting in the Seventies* report.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] These included the introduction of correspondents into news bulletins where previously only a newsreader would present, as well as the inclusion of content gathered in the preparation process.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] New programmes were also added to the daily schedule, *PM* and *The World Tonight* as part of the plan for the station to become a "wholly speech network".
[src:arkive/bbc-news] *Newsbeat* launched as the news service on Radio 1 on 10 September 1973.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] On 23 September 1974, a teletext system which was launched to bring news content on television screens using text only was launched.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Engineers originally began developing such a system to bring news to deaf viewers, but the system was expanded.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The Ceefax service became much more diverse before it ceased on 23 October 2012: it not only had subtitling for all channels, it also gave information such as weather, flight times and film reviews.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] By the end of the decade, the practice of shooting on film for inserts in news broadcasts was declining, with the introduction of ENG technology into the UK.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The equipment would gradually become less cumbersome – the BBC's first attempts had been using a Philips colour camera with backpack base station and separate portable Sony U-matic recorder in the latter half of the decade.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In 1980, the Iranian Embassy Siege had been shot electronically by the BBC Television News Outside broadcasting team, and the work of reporter Kate Adie, broadcasting live from Prince's Gate, was nominated for BAFTA actuality coverage, but this time beaten by ITN for the 1980 award.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The first BBC breakfast television programme, *Breakfast Time* also launched during the 1980s, on 17 January 1983 from Lime Grove Studio E and two weeks before its ITV rival TV-am.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Frank Bough, Selina Scott, and Nick Ross helped to wake viewers with a relaxed style of presenting.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The *Six O'Clock News* first aired on 3 September 1984, eventually becoming the most watched news programme in the UK (however, since 2006 it has been overtaken by the *BBC News at Ten*).
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In October 1984, images of millions of people starving to death in the Ethiopian famine were shown in Michael Buerk's *Six O'Clock News* reports.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The BBC News crew were the first to document the famine, with Buerk's report on 23 October describing it as "a biblical famine in the 20th century" and "the closest thing to hell on Earth".
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The BBC News report shocked Britain, motivating its citizens to inundate relief agencies, such as Save the Children, with donations, and to bring global attention to the crisis in Ethiopia.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The news report was also watched by Bob Geldof, who would organise the charity single "Do They Know It's Christmas?" to raise money for famine relief followed by the Live Aid concert in July 1985.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Starting in 1981, the BBC gave a common theme to its main news bulletins with new electronic titles–a set of computer-animated "stripes" forming a circle on a red background with a "BBC News" typescript appearing below the circle graphics, and a theme tune consisting of brass and keyboards.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The *Nine* used a similar (striped) number 9.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The red background was replaced by a blue from 1985 until 1987.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In 1987, John Birt resurrected the practice of correspondents working for both TV and radio with the introduction of bi-media journalism.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] During the 1990s, a wider range of services began to be offered by BBC News, with the split of BBC World Service Television to become BBC World (news and current affairs), and BBC Prime (light entertainment).
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Content for a 24-hour news channel was thus required, followed in 1997 with the launch of domestic equivalent BBC News 24.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Rather than set bulletins, ongoing reports and coverage was needed to keep both channels functioning and meant a greater emphasis in budgeting for both was necessary.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In 1998, after 66 years at Broadcasting House, the **BBC Radio News** operation moved to BBC Television Centre.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] New technology, provided by Silicon Graphics, came into use in 1993 for a re-launch of the main BBC 1 bulletins, creating a virtual set which appeared to be much larger than it was physically.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The relaunch also brought all bulletins into the same style of set with only small changes in colouring, titles, and music to differentiate each.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] A computer generated cut-glass sculpture of the BBC coat of arms was the centrepiece of the programme titles until the large scale corporate rebranding of news services in 1999.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In November 1997, BBC News Online was launched, following individual webpages for major news events such as the 1996 Olympic Games, 1997 general election, and the death of Princess Diana.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In 1999, the biggest relaunch occurred, with BBC One bulletins, BBC World, BBC News 24, and BBC News Online all adopting a common style.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] One of the most significant changes was the gradual adoption of the corporate image by the BBC regional news programmes, giving a common style across local, national and international BBC television news.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] This also included *Newyddion*, the main news programme of Welsh language channel S4C, produced by BBC News Wales.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Following the relaunch of BBC News in 1999, regional headlines were included at the start of the BBC One news bulletins in 2000.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The English regions did however lose five minutes at the end of their bulletins, due to a new headline round-up at 18:55.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] 2000 also saw the *Nine O'Clock News* moved to the later time of 22:00.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] This was in response to ITN who had just moved their popular *News at Ten* programme to 23:00.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] ITN briefly returned *News at Ten* but following poor ratings when head-to-head against the BBC's *Ten O'Clock News*, the ITN bulletin was moved to 22.30, where it remained until 14 January 2008.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The retirement in 2009 of Peter Sissons and departure of Michael Buerk from the *Ten O'Clock News* led to changes in the BBC One bulletin presenting team on 20 January 2003.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The *Six O'Clock News* became double headed with George Alagiah and Sophie Raworth after Huw Edwards and Fiona Bruce moved to present the *Ten*.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] A new set design featuring a projected fictional newsroom backdrop was introduced, followed on 16 February 2004 by new programme titles to match those of BBC News 24.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC News 24 and BBC World introduced a new style of presentation in December 2003, that was slightly altered on 5 July 2004 to mark 50 years of BBC Television News.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] On 7 March 2005 director general Mark Thompson launched the "Creative Futures" project to restructure the organisation.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The individual positions of editor of the *One* and *Six O'Clock News* were replaced by a new daytime position in November 2005.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Kevin Bakhurst became the first Controller of BBC News 24, replacing the position of editor.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Amanda Farnsworth became daytime editor while Craig Oliver was later named editor of the *Ten O'Clock News*.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Bulletins received new titles and a new set design in May 2006, to allow for *Breakfast* to move into the main studio for the first time since 1997.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The new set featured Barco videowall screens with a background of the London skyline used for main bulletins and originally an image of cirrus clouds against a blue sky for *Breakfast*.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] This was later replaced following viewer criticism.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The studio bore similarities with the ITN-produced ITV News in 2004, though ITN uses a CSO virtual studio rather than the actual screens at BBC News.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC News became part of a new BBC Journalism group in November 2006 as part of a restructuring of the BBC.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The then-Director of BBC News, Helen Boaden reported to the then-Deputy Director-General and head of the journalism group, Mark Byford until he was made redundant in 2010.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] On 18 October 2007, ED Mark Thompson announced a six-year plan, "Delivering Creative Futures" (based on his project begun in March 2005), merging the television current affairs department into a new "News Programmes" division.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Thompson's announcement, in response to a £2 billion shortfall in funding, would, he said, deliver "a smaller but fitter BBC" in the digital age, by cutting its payroll and, in 2013, selling Television Centre.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The various separate newsrooms for television, radio and online operations were merged into a single multimedia newsroom.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Programme making within the newsrooms was brought together to form a multimedia programme making department.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC World Service director Peter Horrocks said that the changes would achieve efficiency at a time of cost-cutting at the BBC.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In his blog, he wrote that by using the same resources across the various broadcast media meant fewer stories could be covered, or by following more stories, there would be fewer ways to broadcast them.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] A new graphics and video playout system was introduced for production of television bulletins in January 2007.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] This coincided with a new structure to BBC World News bulletins, editors favouring a section devoted to analysing the news stories reported on.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The first new BBC News bulletin since the *Six O'Clock News* was announced in July 2007 following a successful trial in the Midlands.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The summary, lasting 90 seconds, has been broadcast at 20:00 on weekdays since December 2007 and bears similarities with *60 Seconds* on BBC Three, but also includes headlines from the various BBC regions and a weather summary.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] As part of a long-term cost cutting programme, bulletins were renamed the *BBC News at One*, *Six* and *Ten* respectively in April 2008 while BBC News 24 was renamed BBC News and moved into the same studio as the bulletins at BBC Television Centre.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC World was renamed *BBC World News* and regional news programmes were also updated with the new presentation style, designed by Lambie-Nairn.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] 2008 also saw tri-media introduced across TV, radio, and online.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The studio moves also meant that Studio N9, previously used for BBC World, was closed, and operations moved to the previous studio of BBC News 24.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Studio N9 was later refitted to match the new branding, and was used for the BBC's UK local elections and European elections coverage in early June 2009.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] A strategy review of the BBC in March 2010, confirmed that having "the best journalism in the world" would form one of five key editorial policies, as part of changes subject to public consultation and BBC Trust approval.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] After a period of suspension in late 2012, Helen Boaden ceased to be the Director of BBC News.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] On 16 April 2013, incoming BBC Director-General Tony Hall named James Harding, a former editor of *The Times* of London newspaper as Director of News and Current Affairs.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] From August 2012 to March 2013, all news operations moved from Television Centre to new facilities in the refurbished and extended Broadcasting House, in Portland Place.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The move began in October 2012, and also included the BBC World Service, which moved from Bush House following the expiry of the BBC's lease.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] This new extension to the north and east, referred to as "New Broadcasting House", includes several new state-of-the-art radio and television studios centred around an 11-storey atrium.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The move began with the domestic programme *The Andrew Marr Show* on 2 September 2012, and concluded with the move of the BBC News channel and domestic news bulletins on 18 March 2013.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The newsroom houses all domestic bulletins and programmes on both television and radio, as well as the BBC World Service international radio networks and the BBC World News international television channel.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC News and CBS News established an editorial and newsgathering partnership in 2017, replacing an earlier long-standing partnership between BBC News and ABC News.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In an October 2018 Simmons Research survey of 38 news organisations, BBC News was ranked the fourth most trusted news organisation by Americans, behind CBS News, ABC News and *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In January 2020 the BBC announced a BBC News savings target of £80 million per year by 2022, involving about 450 staff reductions from the current 6,000.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC director of news and current affairs Fran Unsworth said there would be further moves toward digital broadcasting, in part to attract back a youth audience, and more pooling of reporters to stop separate teams covering the same news.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] A further 70 staff reductions were announced in July 2020.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC Three began airing the news programme *The Catch Up* in February 2022.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] It is presented by Levi Jouavel, Kirsty Grant, and Callum Tulley and aims to get the channel's target audience (16 to 34-year olds) to make sense of the world around them while also highlighting optimistic stories.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Compared to its predecessor *60 Seconds*, *The Catch Up* is three times longer, running for about three minutes and not airing during weekends.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] According to its annual report as of December 2021, India has the largest number of people using BBC services in the world.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In May 2025, following the earthquake that hit Myanmar and Thailand, a television news bulletin (BBC News Myanmar) from the Burmese service using a vacated Voice of America satellite frequency began its broadcasts.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Government officials including Cyprus president Nikos Christodoulides and European lawmakers began responding to the investigation's findings in less than 24 hours, calling for reforms and launching probes.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC News is responsible for the news programmes and documentary content on the BBC's general television channels, as well as the news coverage on the BBC News Channel in the UK, and 22 hours of programming for the corporation's international BBC World News channel.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Coverage for BBC Parliament is carried out on behalf of the BBC at Millbank Studios, though BBC News provides editorial and journalistic content.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC News content is also output onto the BBC's digital interactive television services under the BBC Red Button brand, and until 2012, on the Ceefax teletext system.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The music on all BBC television news programmes was introduced in 1999 and composed by David Lowe.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] It was part of the re-branding which commenced in 1999 and features 'BBC Pips'.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The general theme was used on bulletins on BBC One, News 24, BBC World and local news programmes in the BBC's Nations and Regions.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Lowe was also responsible for the music on Radio One's *Newsbeat*.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The theme has had several changes since 1999, the latest in March 2013.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The BBC Verify service was launched in 2023 to fact-check news stories, followed by BBC Verify Live in 2025.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC Radio News produces bulletins for the BBC's national radio stations and provides content for local BBC radio stations via the General News Service (GNS), a BBC-internal news distribution service.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC News does not produce the BBC's regional news bulletins, which are produced individually by the BBC nations and regions themselves.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The BBC World Service broadcasts to some 150 million people in English as well as 27 languages across the globe.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC Radio News is a patron of the Radio Academy.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC News Online is the BBC's news website.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Launched in November 1997, it is one of the most popular news websites, with 1.2 billion website visits in April 2021, as well as being used by 60% of the UK's internet users for news.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The website contains international news coverage as well as entertainment, sport, science, and political news.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Mobile apps for Android, iOS and Windows Phone systems have been provided since 2010.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Many television and radio programmes are also available to view on the BBC iPlayer and BBC Sounds services.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The BBC News channel is also available to view 24 hours a day, while video and radio clips are also available within online news articles.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In October 2019, BBC News Online launched a mirror on the dark web anonymity network Tor in an effort to circumvent censorship.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The BBC is required by its charter to be free from both political and commercial influence and answers only to its viewers and listeners.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] This political objectivity is sometimes questioned.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] For instance, *The Daily Telegraph* (3 August 2005) carried a letter from the KGB defector Oleg Gordievsky, referring to it as "The Red Service".
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Books have been written on the subject, including anti-BBC works like *Truth Betrayed* by W J West and *The Truth Twisters* by Richard Deacon.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The BBC has been accused of bias by Conservative MPs.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The BBC's Editorial Guidelines on Politics and Public Policy state that while "the voices and opinions of opposition parties must be routinely aired and challenged", "the government of the day will often be the primary source of news".
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The BBC is regularly accused by the government of the day of bias in favour of the opposition and, by the opposition, of bias in favour of the government.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Similarly, during times of war, the BBC is often accused by the UK government, or by strong supporters of British military campaigns, of being overly sympathetic to the view of the enemy.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] An edition of *Newsnight* at the start of the Falklands War in 1982 was described as "almost treasonable" by John Page, MP, who objected to Peter Snow saying "if we believe the British".
[src:arkive/bbc-news] During the first Gulf War, critics of the BBC took to using the satirical name "Baghdad Broadcasting Corporation".
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Conversely, some of those who style themselves anti-establishment in the United Kingdom or who oppose foreign wars have accused the BBC of pro-establishment bias or of refusing to give an outlet to "anti-war" voices.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Following the 2003 invasion of Iraq, a study by the Cardiff University School of Journalism of the reporting of the war found that nine out of 10 references to weapons of mass destruction during the war assumed that Iraq possessed them, and only one in 10 questioned this assumption.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] It also found that, out of the main British broadcasters covering the war, the BBC was the most likely to use the British government and military as its source.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] It was also the least likely to use independent sources, like the Red Cross, who were more critical of the war.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] When it came to reporting Iraqi casualties, the study found fewer reports on the BBC than on the other three main channels.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The report's author, Justin Lewis, wrote "Far from revealing an anti-war BBC, our findings tend to give credence to those who criticised the BBC for being too sympathetic to the government in its war coverage.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Prominent BBC appointments are constantly assessed by the British media and political establishment for signs of political bias.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The appointment of Greg Dyke as Director-General was highlighted by press sources because Dyke was a Labour Party member and former activist, as well as a friend of Tony Blair.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Mark Thompson, former Director-General of the BBC, admitted the organisation has been biased "towards the left" in the past.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] He said, "In the BBC I joined 30 years ago, there was, in much of current affairs, in terms of people's personal politics, which were quite vocal, a massive bias to the left".
[src:arkive/bbc-news] He then added, "The organization did struggle then with impartiality.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Now it is a completely different generation.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Following the EU referendum in 2016, some critics suggested that the BBC was biased in favour of leaving the EU.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] For instance, in 2018, the BBC received complaints from people who took issue that the BBC was not sufficiently covering anti-Brexit marches while giving smaller-scale events hosted by former UKIP leader Nigel Farage more airtime.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] On the other hand, a poll released by YouGov showed that 45% of people who voted to leave the EU thought that the BBC was 'actively anti-Brexit' compared to 13% of the same kinds of voters who think the BBC is pro-Brexit.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In 2008, the BBC Hindi was criticised by some Indian outlets for referring to the terrorists who carried out the 2008 Mumbai attacks as "gunmen".
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The response to this added to prior criticism from some Indian commentators suggesting that the BBC may have an Indophobic bias.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In March 2015, the BBC was criticised for a BBC *Storyville* documentary interviewing one of the rapists in India.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In spite of a ban ordered by the Indian High court, the BBC still aired the documentary "India's Daughter" outside India.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC News was at the centre of a political controversy following the 2003 invasion of Iraq.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The government denounced the reports and accused the corporation of poor journalism.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In subsequent weeks the corporation stood by the report, saying that it had a reliable source.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Following intense media speculation, David Kelly was named in the press as the source for Gilligan's story on 9 July 2003.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Kelly was found dead, by suicide, in a field close to his home early on 18 July.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] An inquiry led by Lord Hutton was announced by the British government the following day to investigate the circumstances leading to Kelly's death, concluding that "Dr.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In his report on 28 January 2004, Lord Hutton concluded that Gilligan's original accusation was "unfounded" and the BBC's editorial and management processes were "defective".
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In particular, it specifically criticised the chain of management that caused the BBC to defend its story.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The BBC Director of News, Richard Sambrook, the report said, had accepted Gilligan's word that his story was accurate in spite of his notes being incomplete.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Davies had then told the BBC Board of Governors that he was happy with the story and told the Prime Minister that a satisfactory internal inquiry had taken place.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The Board of Governors, under the chairman's, Gavyn Davies, guidance, accepted that further investigation of the Government's complaints were unnecessary.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Because of the criticism in the Hutton report, Davies resigned on the day of publication.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC News faced an important test, reporting on itself with the publication of the report, but by common consent (of the Board of Governors) managed this "independently, impartially and honestly".
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Davies' resignation was followed by the resignation of Director General, Greg Dyke, the following day, and the resignation of Gilligan on 30 January.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] While undoubtedly a traumatic experience for the corporation, an ICM poll in April 2003 indicated that it had sustained its position as the best and most trusted provider of news.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The BBC has faced accusations of holding both anti-Israel and anti-Palestine bias.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] However two large independent studies, one conducted by Loughborough University and the other by Glasgow University's Media Group concluded that Israeli perspectives are given greater coverage.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Critics of the BBC argue that the Balen Report proves systematic bias against Israel in headline news programming.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The *Daily Mail* and *The Daily Telegraph* criticised the BBC for spending hundreds of thousands of British tax payers' pounds from preventing the report being released to the public.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] An independent panel appointed by the BBC Trust was set up in 2006 to review the impartiality of the BBC's coverage of the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In some ways the picture is incomplete and, in that sense, misleading." It notes that, "the failure to convey adequately the disparity in the Israeli and Palestinian experience, [reflects] the fact that one side is in control and the other lives under occupation".
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Writing in the *Financial Times*, Philip Stephens, one of the panellists, later accused the BBC's director-general, Mark Thompson, of misrepresenting the panel's conclusions.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] He further opined "My sense is that BBC news reporting has also lost a once iron-clad commitment to objectivity and a necessary respect for the democratic process.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Mark Thompson published a rebuttal in the FT the next day.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Walker argues that the independent inquiry was flawed for two reasons.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Firstly, because the time period over which it was conducted (August 2005 to January 2006) surrounded the Israeli withdrawal from Gaza and Ariel Sharon's stroke, which produced more positive coverage than usual.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Furthermore, he wrote, the inquiry only looked at the BBC's domestic coverage, and excluded output on the BBC World Service and BBC World.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Tom Gross, writing for the *National Review*, criticised the BBC's coverage of Hamas suicide bombers, and its invitations of Jenny Tonge and Tom Paulin as guest commentators, claiming that Paulin had "compared Jewish settlers to Nazis".
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Paulin had previously stated that Israeli settlers should be "shot dead", and said he could "understand how suicide bombers feel".
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The BBC also faced criticism for not airing a Disasters Emergency Committee aid appeal for Palestinians who suffered in Gaza during 22-day war there between late 2008 and early 2009.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Most other major UK broadcasters did air this appeal, but rival Sky News did not.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] British journalist Julie Burchill has accused BBC of creating a "climate of fear" for British Jews over its "excessive coverage" of Israel compared to other nations.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In light of the Gaza war, the BBC suspended seven Arab journalists over allegations of expressing support for Hamas via social media.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC and ABC share video segments and reporters as needed in producing their newscasts. with the BBC showing *ABC World News Tonight with David Muir* in the UK.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] However, in July 2017, the BBC announced a new partnership with CBS News allows both organisations to share video, editorial content, and additional newsgathering resources in New York, London, Washington and around the world.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC News subscribes to wire services from leading international agencies including PA Media (formerly Press Association), Reuters, and Agence France-Presse.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In April 2017, the BBC dropped Associated Press in favour of an enhanced service from AFP.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC News reporters and broadcasts are now and have in the past been banned in several countries primarily for reporting which has been unfavourable to the ruling government.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] For example, correspondents were banned by the former apartheid regime of South Africa.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The BBC was banned in Zimbabwe under Mugabe for eight years as a terrorist organisation until being allowed to operate again over a year after the 2008 elections.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The BBC was banned in Burma (officially Myanmar) after their coverage and commentary on anti-government protests there in September 2007.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The ban was lifted four years later in September 2011.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Other cases have included Uzbekistan, China, and Pakistan.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] BBC Persian, the BBC's Persian language news site, was blocked from the Iranian internet in 2006.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The BBC News website was made available in China again in March 2008, but as of October 2014, was blocked again.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In June 2015, the Rwandan government placed an indefinite ban on BBC broadcasts following the airing of a controversial documentary regarding the 1994 Rwandan genocide, *Rwanda's Untold Story*, broadcast on BBC2 on 1 October 2014.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] The UK's Foreign Office recognised "the hurt caused in Rwanda by some parts of the documentary".
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In February 2017, reporters from the BBC (as well as the *Daily Mail*, *The New York Times*, Politico, CNN, and others) were denied access to a United States White House briefing.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] In 2017, BBC India was banned for a period of five years from covering all national parks and sanctuaries in India.
[src:arkive/bbc-news] Following the withdrawal of CGTN's UK broadcaster licence on 4 February 2021 by Ofcom, China banned BBC News from airing in China.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The **British Broadcasting Corporation** (**BBC**) is a British public service broadcaster that serves as the primary national public broadcasting company of the United Kingdom, headquartered at Broadcasting House in London, England.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Originally established in 1922 as the British Broadcasting Company, it evolved into its current state with its current name on 1 January 1927.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] It is the oldest and largest local and global broadcaster by stature and by number of employees, with a total staff of 21,000.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The BBC was established under a royal charter, and operates under an agreement with the secretary of state for culture, media and sport.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Its work is funded principally by an annual television licence fee which is charged to all British households, companies, and organisations using any type of equipment to receive or record live television broadcasts or to use the BBC's streaming service, iPlayer.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The fee is set by the British government, agreed by Parliament, and is used to fund the BBC's radio, TV, and online services covering the nations and regions of the UK.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Since 1 April 2014, it has also funded the BBC World Service (launched in 1932 as the BBC Empire Service), which broadcasts in 43 languages as of 2026.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Some of the BBC's revenue comes from its commercial subsidiary BBC Studios (formerly BBC Worldwide), which sells BBC programs and services internationally and also distributes the BBC's international 24-hour English-language news services BBC News, and from BBC.com, provided by BBC Global News Ltd.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Since its formation on 18 October 1922, the BBC has played a prominent role in British life and culture.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] It is sometimes informally referred to as **the Beeb** or **Auntie**.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 1923 it launched *Radio Times* (subtitled "The official organ of the BBC"), the first broadcast listings magazine; the 1988 Christmas edition sold 11 million copies, the biggest-selling edition of any British magazine in history.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Britain's first live public broadcast was made from the factory of Marconi Company in Chelmsford in June 1920.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] It was sponsored by the *Daily Mail*'s Alfred Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Northcliffe and featured the famous Australian soprano Dame Nellie Melba.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The Melba broadcast caught the people's imagination and marked a turning point in the British public's attitude to radio.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] However, this public enthusiasm was not shared in official circles where such broadcasts were held to interfere with important military and civil communications.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] By late 1920, the pressure from these quarters and uneasiness among the staff of the licensing authority, the General Post Office (GPO), was sufficient to lead to a ban on further Chelmsford broadcasts.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] But by 1922 the GPO had received nearly 100 broadcast licence requests and moved to rescind its ban in the wake of a petition by 63 wireless societies with over 3,000 members.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] John Reith, a Scottish Calvinist, was appointed its general manager in December 1922 a few weeks after the company made its first official broadcast.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Stanton Jefferies was its first director of music.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The company was to be financed by a royalty on the sale of BBC wireless receiving sets from approved domestic manufacturers.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] To this day, the BBC aims to follow the Reithian directive to "inform, educate and entertain".
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The financial arrangements soon proved inadequate.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Set sales were disappointing as amateurs made their own receivers and listeners bought rival unlicensed sets.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] By mid-1923, discussions between the GPO and the BBC had become deadlocked and the Postmaster General commissioned a review of broadcasting by the Sykes Committee.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The committee recommended a short-term reorganisation of licence fees with improved enforcement to address the BBC's immediate financial distress, and an increased share of the licence revenue split between it and the GPO.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] This was to be followed by a simple 10 shillings licence fee to fund broadcasts.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The BBC's broadcasting monopoly was made explicit for the duration of its current broadcast licence, as was the prohibition on advertising.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] To avoid competition with newspapers, Fleet Street persuaded the government to ban news bulletins before 7 pm and the BBC was required to source all news from external wire services.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The *Radio Times*, the world's first and longest-running radio and television listings magazine, was launched by Reith in September 1923.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The first edition, subtitled "The official organ of the BBC", was priced at tuppence (two pence) on newsstands, and quickly sold out its run of a quarter of a million copies.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Mid-1925 found the future of broadcasting under further consideration, this time by the Crawford committee.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] By now the BBC, under Reith's leadership, had forged a consensus favouring a continuation of the unified (monopoly) broadcasting service, but more money was still required to finance rapid expansion.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Wireless manufacturers were anxious to exit the loss-making consortium, and Reith was keen that the BBC be seen as a public service rather than a commercial enterprise.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The recommendations of the Crawford Committee were published in March the following year and were still under consideration by the GPO when the 1926 United Kingdom general strike broke out in May.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The strike temporarily interrupted newspaper production, and with restrictions on news bulletins waived, the BBC suddenly became the primary source of news for the duration of the crisis.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The crisis placed the BBC in a delicate position.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] On the one hand Reith was acutely aware that the government might exercise its right to commandeer the BBC at any time as a mouthpiece of the government if the BBC were to step out of line, but on the other he was anxious to maintain public trust by appearing to be acting independently.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The government was divided on how to handle the BBC, but ended up trusting Reith, whose opposition to the strike mirrored the PM's own.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Although Winston Churchill in particular wanted to commandeer the BBC to use it "to the best possible advantage", Reith wrote that Stanley Baldwin's government wanted to be able to say "that they did not commandeer [the BBC], but they know that they can trust us not to be really impartial".
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Thus the BBC was granted sufficient leeway to pursue the government's objectives largely in a manner of its own choosing.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Supporters of the strike nicknamed the BBC the BFC for British Falsehood Company.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Reith personally announced the end of the strike which he marked by reciting from Blake's "Jerusalem" signifying that England had been saved.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] While the BBC tends to characterise its coverage of the general strike by emphasising the positive impression created by its balanced coverage of the views of government and strikers, Seaton has characterised the episode as the invention of "modern propaganda in its British form".
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Reith argued that trust gained by 'authentic impartial news' could then be used.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Impartial news was not necessarily an end in itself.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The British Broadcasting Corporation came into existence on 1 January 1927, and Reith – newly knighted – was appointed its first director general.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] To represent its purpose and (stated) values, the new corporation adopted the coat of arms, including the motto "Nation shall speak peace unto Nation".
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] British radio audiences had little choice apart from BBC's programming approach.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Reith was viewed as taking a moralistic approach as an executive, aiming to broadcast "all that is best in every department of human knowledge, endeavour and achievement", and putting the programming in moral or ethical terms, advocating "a high moral tone" as "obviously of paramount importance".
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Reith succeeded in building a high wall against a more tabloid, free-for-all in radio aimed at merely attracting the largest audience (and advertising revenue).
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] There was no paid advertising on the BBC; all the revenue came from a tax on receiving sets.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Highbrow audiences, however, greatly enjoyed it.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] At a time when American, Australian and Canadian stations were drawing huge audiences cheering for their local teams with the broadcast of baseball, rugby and hockey, the BBC emphasised service for a national rather than a regional audience.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Boat races were well covered along with tennis and horse racing, but the BBC was reluctant to spend its severely limited air time on long football or cricket games, regardless of their popularity.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] John Reith and the BBC, with support from the Crown, determined the universal needs of the people of Britain and broadcast content according to these perceived standards.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Reith effectively censored anything that he felt would be harmful, directly or indirectly.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] While recounting his time with the BBC in 1935, Raymond Postgate claims that BBC broadcasters were made to submit a draft of their potential broadcast for approval.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] It was expected that they tailored their content to accommodate the modest, church-going elderly or a member of the Clergy.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Until 1928, entertainers broadcasting on the BBC, both singers and "talkers" were expected to avoid biblical quotations, Clerical impersonations and references, references to drink or Prohibition in the United States, vulgar and doubtful matter and political allusions.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The BBC excluded popular foreign music and musicians from its broadcasts, while promoting British alternatives.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] On 5 March 1928, Stanley Baldwin, the Prime Minister, maintained the censorship of editorial opinions on public policy, but allowed the BBC to address matters of religious, political or industrial controversy.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The resulting political "talk series", designed to inform England on political issues, were criticised by members of parliament, including Winston Churchill, David Lloyd George and Sir Austen Chamberlain.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Those who opposed these chats claimed that they silence the opinions of those in Parliament who are not nominated by Party Leaders or Party Whips, thus stifling independent, non-official views.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In October 1932, the policemen of the Metropolitan Police Federation marched in protest at a proposed pay cut.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Fearing dissent within the police force and public support for the movement, the BBC censored its coverage of the events, only broadcasting official statements from the government.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Throughout the 1930s political broadcasts had been monitored by the BBC.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 1935, the BBC censored the broadcasts of Oswald Mosley and Harry Pollitt.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Mosley was a leader of the British Union of Fascists, and Pollitt a leader of the Communist Party of Great Britain.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] They were contracted to provide a series of five broadcasts on their parties' politics.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The BBC, in conjunction with The Foreign Office of Britain, suspended this series and ultimately cancelled it without the notice of the public.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 1938, Winston Churchill proposed a series of talks regarding British domestic and foreign politics and affairs but was censored.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The censorship of political discourse by the BBC started the shutdown of the political debate that manifested over the BBC's wartime airwaves.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The Foreign Office maintained that the public should not be aware of their role in the censorship.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] From 1935 to 1939, the BBC attempted to unite the British Empire's radio waves, sending staff to Egypt, Palestine, Newfoundland, Jamaica, India, Canada and South Africa.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Reith visited South Africa, lobbying for state-run radio programmes accepted by South African Parliament in 1936.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] A similar programme was adopted in Canada.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Through collaboration with these state-run broadcasting centres, Reith had an influence on the culture across the empire of Great Britain with his departure from the corporation in 1938.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Experimental television broadcasts were started in 1929 using an electromechanical 30-line system developed by John Logie Baird.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The superiority of the electronic system saw the mechanical system dropped early the following year, with the Marconi-EMI system the first fully electronic television system in the world to be used in regular broadcasting.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The success of broadcasting provoked animosities between the BBC and well-established media such as theatres, concert halls and the recording industry.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] By 1929, the BBC complained that the agents of many comedians refused to sign contracts for broadcasting, because they feared it harmed the artist "by making his material stale" and that it "reduces the value of the artist as a visible music-hall performer".
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Television broadcasting was suspended from 1 September 1939 to 7 June 1946, during World War II, and it was left to BBC Radio broadcasters such as Reginald Foort to keep the nation's spirits up.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The BBC moved most of its radio operations out of London, initially to Bristol, and then to Bedford.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] BBC employees during the war included George Orwell who spent two years with the broadcaster.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] During his role as prime minister during the war, Winston Churchill delivered 33 major wartime speeches by radio, all of which were carried by the BBC within the UK.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] On 18 June 1940, French general Charles de Gaulle, in exile in London as the leader of the Free French, made a speech, broadcast by the BBC, urging the French people not to capitulate to the Nazis.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In October 1940, Princesses Elizabeth and Margaret made their first radio broadcast for the BBC's *Children's Hour*, addressing other children who had been evacuated from cities.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 1938 John Reith and the Government of the United Kingdom, specifically the Ministry of Information which had been set up for WWII, designed a censorship apparatus for the inevitability of war.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Due to the BBC's advancements in shortwave radio technology, the corporation could broadcast across the world during the Second World War.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Within Europe, the BBC European Service would gather intelligence and information regarding the current events of the war in English.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Regional BBC workers, based on their regional geo-political climate, would then further censor the material their broadcasts would cover.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Nothing was to be added outside the preordained news items.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] For example, the BBC Polish Service was heavily censored due to fears of jeopardising relations with the Soviet Union.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Controversial topics, i.e. the contested Polish and Soviet border, the deportation of Polish citizens, the arrests of Polish Home Army members and the Katyn massacre, were not included in Polish broadcasts.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] American radio broadcasts were broadcast across Europe on BBC channels.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] This material also passed through the BBC's censorship office, which surveilled and edited American coverage of British affairs.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] By 1940, across all BBC broadcasts, music by composers from enemy nations was censored.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In total, 99 German, 38 Austrian and 38 Italian composers were censored.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The BBC argued that like the Italian or German languages, listeners would be irritated by the inclusion of enemy composers.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Any potential broadcasters said to have pacifist, communist or fascist ideologies were not allowed on the BBC's airwaves.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 1937, a MI5 security officer was given a permanent office within the organisation.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] This officer would examine the files of potential political subversives and mark the files of those deemed a security risk to the organisation, blacklisting them.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] This was often done on spurious grounds; even so, the practice would continue and expand during the years of the Cold War.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] There was a widely reported urban myth that, upon resumption of the BBC television service after the war, announcer Leslie Mitchell started by saying, "As I was saying before we were so rudely interrupted ...".
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In fact, the first person to appear when transmission resumed was Jasmine Bligh and the words said were, "Good afternoon, everybody.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Do you remember me, Jasmine Bligh...?" The European Broadcasting Union was formed on 12 February 1950, in Torquay with the BBC among the 23 founding broadcasting organizations.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Competition to the BBC was introduced in 1955, with the commercial and independently operated television network of Independent Television (ITV).
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] However, the BBC monopoly on radio services would persist until 8 October 1973 when under the control of the newly renamed Independent Broadcasting Authority (IBA), the UK's first Independent local radio station, LBC came on-air in the London area.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] BBC2 used the higher resolution 625-line standard which had been standardised across Europe.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] BBC2 was broadcast in colour from 1 July 1967 and was joined by BBC1 and ITV on 15 November 1969.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The 405-line VHF transmissions of BBC1 (and ITV) were continued for compatibility with older television receivers until 1985.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Starting in 1964, a series of pirate radio stations (starting with Radio Caroline) came on the air and forced the British government finally to regulate radio services to permit nationally based advertising-financed services.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In response, the BBC reorganised and renamed their radio channels.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] On 30 September 1967, the Light Programme was split into Radio 1 offering continuous "Popular" music and Radio 2 more "Easy Listening".
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The "Third" programme became Radio 3 offering classical music and cultural programming.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The Home Service became Radio 4 offering news, and non-musical content such as quiz shows, readings, dramas and plays.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] As well as the four national channels, a series of local BBC radio stations were established in 1967, including Radio London.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 1969, the BBC Enterprises department was formed to exploit BBC brands and programmes for commercial spin-off products.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 1979, it became a wholly owned limited company, BBC Enterprises Ltd.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 1974 the BBC's teletext service, Ceefax, was introduced, created initially to provide subtitling, but developed into a news and information service.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 1978, BBC staff went on strike just before the Christmas, thus blocking out the transmission of both channels and amalgamating all four radio stations into one.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Since the deregulation of the UK television and radio market in the 1980s, the BBC has faced increased competition from the commercial sector (and from the advertiser-funded public service broadcaster Channel 4), especially on satellite television, cable television, and digital television services.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In the late 1980s, the BBC began a process of divestment by spinning off and selling parts of its organisation.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 1988, it sold off the Hulton Press Library, a photographic archive which had been acquired from the *Picture Post* magazine by the BBC in 1957.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The archive was sold to Brian Deutsch and is now owned by Getty Images.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 1987, the BBC decided to centralise its operations by the management team with the radio and television divisions joining forces together for the first time, the activities of the news and currents departments and coordinated jointly under the new directorate.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] During the 1990s, this process continued with the separation of certain operational arms of the corporation into autonomous but wholly owned subsidiaries, with the aim of generating additional revenue for programme-making.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] BBC Enterprises was reorganised and relaunched in 1995, as BBC Worldwide Ltd.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 1998, BBC studios, outside broadcasts, post production, design, costumes and wigs were spun off into BBC Resources Ltd.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The BBC Research & Development has played a major part in the development of broadcasting and recording techniques.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The BBC was also responsible for the development of the NICAM stereo standard.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The new station would be a news and sport station.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 1997, BBC News 24, a rolling news channel, launched on digital television services, and the following year, BBC Choice was launched as the third general entertainment channel from the BBC.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The BBC also purchased The Parliamentary Channel, which was renamed BBC Parliament.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 1999, BBC Knowledge launched as a multimedia channel, with services available on the newly launched BBC Text digital teletext service (later rebranded as BBC Red Button), and on BBC Online.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The channel had an educational aim, which was modified later on in its life to offer documentaries.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 2002 several television and radio channels were reorganised.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] BBC Knowledge was replaced by BBC Four and became the BBC's arts and documentaries channel.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] CBBC, which had been a programming strand as Children's BBC since 1985, was split into CBBC and CBeebies, for younger children, with both new services getting a digital channel: the CBBC Channel and CBeebies Channel.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In addition to the television channels, new digital radio stations were created: 1Xtra, 6 Music and Radio 4 Extra.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] BBC 1Xtra was a sister station to Radio 1 and specialised in modern black music, BBC 6 Music specialised in alternative music genres and BBC7 specialised in archive, speech and children's programming.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 2008, another channel was launched, BBC Alba, a Scottish Gaelic service.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 2006 BBC HD was launched as an experimental service, becoming official in December 2007.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The channel broadcast HD simulcasts of programmes on BBC One, BBC Two, BBC Three and BBC Four as well as repeats of some older programmes in HD.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 2010, an HD simulcast of BBC One launched: BBC One HD.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The channel uses HD versions of BBC One's schedule and uses upscaled versions of programmes not currently produced in HD.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The BBC HD channel closed in March 2013 and was replaced by BBC Two HD in the same month.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The 2004 Hutton Inquiry and the subsequent report raised questions about the BBC's journalistic standards and its impartiality.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] This led to resignations of senior management members at the time including the then Director General, Greg Dyke.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In January 2007, the BBC released minutes of the board meeting which led to Greg Dyke's resignation.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The BBC's IT, telephony and broadcast technology were brought together as BBC Technology Ltd in 2001, and the division was later sold to the German company Siemens IT Solutions and Services (SIS).
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] SIS was subsequently acquired from Siemens by the French company Atos.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Further divestments included BBC Books (sold to Random House in 2006); BBC Outside Broadcasts Ltd (sold in 2008 to Satellite Information Services); Costumes and Wigs (stock sold in 2008 to Angels Costumes); and BBC Magazines (sold to Immediate Media Company in 2011).
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] After the sales of OBs and costumes, the remainder of BBC Resources was reorganised as BBC Studios and Post Production, which continues today as a wholly owned subsidiary of the BBC.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] A strike in May 2005 by more than 11,000 BBC workers over a proposal to cut 4,000 jobs and to privatise parts of the BBC, disrupted much of the BBC's regular programming.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The blueprint for the future of the BBC resulting from the project was published ion 25 April 2006.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] On 18 October 2007, Thompson announced a six-year plan, "Delivering Creative Futures", which included merging the television current affairs department into a new "News Programmes" division.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The plans included a reduction in posts of 2,500; including 1,800 redundancies, consolidating news operations, reducing programming output by 10% and selling off the flagship Television Centre building in London.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] On 20 October 2010 the Chancellor of the Exchequer George Osborne announced that the television licence fee would be frozen at its current level until the end of the current charter in 2016.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The same announcement revealed that the BBC would take on the full cost of running the BBC World Service and the BBC Monitoring service from the Foreign, Commonwealth and Development Office, and partially finance the Welsh broadcaster S4C.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] BBC HD was closed on 26 March 2013, and replaced with an HD simulcast of BBC Two; however, flagship programmes, other channels and full funding for CBBC and CBeebies would be retained.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Numerous BBC facilities have been sold off, including New Broadcasting House on Wilmslow Road in Manchester.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Many major departments have been relocated to Broadcasting House in central London and MediaCityUK in Salford, particularly since the closure of BBC Television Centre in March 2013.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] On 16 February 2016, the BBC Three television service was discontinued and replaced by a digital outlet under the same name, targeting its young adult audience with web series and other content.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Under the new royal charter instituted in 2017, the corporation must publish an annual report to Ofcom, outlining its plans and public service obligations for the next year.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In its 2017–18 report, released July 2017, the BBC announced plans to "re-invent" its output to better compete against commercial streaming services such as Netflix.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Since 2017, the BBC has also funded the Local Democracy Reporting Service, with up to 165 journalists employed by independent news organisations to report on local democracy issues on a pooled basis.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 2016 the BBC Director General Tony Hall announced a savings target of £800 million per year by 2021, which is about 23% of annual licence fee revenue.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Having to take on the £700 million cost for free TV licences for the over-75 pensioners, and rapid inflation in drama and sport coverage costs, was given as the reason.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Duplication of management and content spending would be reduced, and there would be a review of BBC News.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In September 2019 the BBC launched the Trusted News Initiative to work with news and social media companies to combat disinformation about national elections.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 2020 the BBC announced a BBC News savings target of £80 million per year by 2022, involving about 520 staff reductions.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The BBC's director of news and current affairs Fran Unsworth said there would be further moves toward digital broadcasting, in part to attract back a youth audience, and more pooling of reporters to stop separate teams covering the same news.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 2020, the BBC reported a £119 million deficit because of delays to cost reduction plans, and the forthcoming ending of the remaining £253 million funding towards pensioner licence fees would increase financial pressures.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In March 2023 the BBC was at the centre of a political row with football pundit Gary Lineker, after he criticised the British government's asylum policy on social media.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Lineker was suspended from his position on *Match of the Day* before being re-instated after receiving overwhelming support from his colleagues.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The scandal was made worse due to the connections between BBC's chairman, Richard Sharp, and the Conservative Party.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In April 2023 Richard Sharp resigned as chairman after a report found he did not disclose potential perceived conflicts of interest in his role in the facilitation of a loan to Prime Minister Boris Johnson.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Dame Elan Closs Stephens was appointed as acting chairwoman on 27 June 2023, and she would lead the BBC board for a year or until a new permanent chair has been appointed.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Samir Shah was subsequently appointed with effect from 4 March 2024.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In October 2024 it was announced that the BBC along with Sky Sports signed a deal to broadcast the 2025–26 season of the Women's Super League campaign.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In May 2025, BBC director general Tim Davie said there were plans to switch off traditional broadcast transmissions in the 2030s to transition to a fully online delivery of programmes.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In November 2025, following the leaking of a report that alleged systemic bias within the BBC, Tim Davie resigned as Director-General along with Deborah Turness as CEO of News within the organisation.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] On 16 December 2025, the UK government considered a green paper of new ways to fund the BBC, such as replacing the television licence with either advertising or a subscription model.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] On 25 March 2026, former Google executive Matt Brittin was appointed as the new Director-General.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] On 15 April 2026, BBC announced cuts up to 2,000 jobs—its largest layoffs in over a decade—to reduce costs by about 10% (around £500 million) over the next two years.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The BBC is a chartered corporation, independent from direct government intervention, with its activities being overseen from April 2017 by the BBC Board and regulated by Ofcom.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The BBC is a public broadcasting company that operates under a royal charter.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The charter is the constitutional basis for the BBC, and sets out the BBC's object, mission and public purposes.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] It emphasises public service, (limited) editorial independence, prohibits advertising on domestic services and proclaims the BBC is to "seek to avoid adverse impacts on competition which are not necessary for the effective fulfilment of the Mission and the promotion of the Public Purposes".
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The charter additionally sets out that the BBC is subject to an additional agreement between it and the Culture Secretary, and that its operating licence is to be set by Ofcom, an external regulatory body.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] It used to be that the Home Secretary be departmental to both the agreement as well as the licence, and regulatory duties fall to the BBC Trust, but the 2017 charter changed those 2007 arrangements.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The charter also outlines the BBC's governance and regulatory arrangements as a statutory corporation, including the role and composition of the BBC Board.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The current charter took effect on 1 January 2017 and is set to expire on 31 December 2027; the agreement being coterminous.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] It replaced the previous governing body, the BBC Trust, which itself had replaced the board of governors in 2007.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The board sets the strategy for the corporation, assesses the performance of the BBC's executive board in delivering the BBC's services, and appoints the director-general.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Ofcom is responsible for the regulation of the BBC.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Samir Shah has served as the chairman since 4 March 2024.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The executive committee is responsible for the day-to-day operations of the broadcaster.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Consisting of senior managers of the BBC, the committee meets once per month and is responsible for operational management and delivery of services within a framework set by the board, and is chaired by the director-general, who is chief executive and (from 1994) editor-in-chief.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] From as early as the 1930s until the 1990s, MI5, the British domestic intelligence service, engaged in the vetting of applicants for BBC jobs, a policy designed to keep out persons deemed subversive.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 1933, BBC executive Colonel Alan Dawnay began to meet the head of MI5, Sir Vernon Kell, to informally trade information; from 1935, a formal arrangement was made whereby job applicants would be secretly vetted by MI5 for their political views (without their knowledge).
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] The BBC took up a policy of denying any suggestion by the press of such a relationship (the very existence of MI5 itself was not officially acknowledged until the Security Service Act 1989).
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] This relationship garnered wider public attention after an article by David Leigh and Paul Lashmar appeared in *The Observer* in August 1985, revealing that MI5 had been vetting appointments, running operations from Room 105 in Broadcasting House.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] At the time of the exposé, the operation was being run by Ronnie Stonham.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] A memo from 1984 revealed that blacklisted organisations included the far-left Communist Party of Great Britain, the Socialist Workers Party, the Workers Revolutionary Party and the Militant tendency, as well as the far-right National Front and the British National Party.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] An association with one of these groups could result in a denial of a job application.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In October 1985 the BBC announced that it would stop the vetting process, except for a few people in top roles, as well as those in charge of Wartime Broadcasting Service emergency broadcasting (in the event of a nuclear war) and staff of the BBC World Service.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] In 1990, following the Security Service Act 1989, vetting was further restricted to those responsible for wartime broadcasting and those with access to secret government information.
[src:arkive/bbc-p01] Michael Hodder, who succeeded Stonham, had the MI5 vetting files sent to the BBC Archives in Reading, Berkshire.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC has the second largest budget of any UK-based broadcaster with an operating expenditure of £4.722 billion in 2013/14 compared with £6.471 billion for Sky UK in 2013/14 and £1.843 billion for ITV in the calendar year 2013.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The principal means of funding the BBC is through the television licence, costing £169.50 per year per household as of April 2024.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Such a licence is required to legally receive broadcast television across the UK, the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] No licence is required to own a television used for other means, or for sound only radio sets (though a separate licence for these was also required for non-TV households until 1971).
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The cost of a television licence is set by the government and enforced by the criminal law.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] A 50% discount is offered to people who are registered blind or severely visually impaired, and the licence is completely free for any household containing anyone aged 75 or over and receiving pension credit.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC pursues its licence fee collection and enforcement under the trading name "TV Licensing".
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The revenue is collected privately by Capita, an outside agency, and is paid into the central government Consolidated Fund, a process defined in the Communications Act 2003.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Funds are then allocated by the Department for Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) and the Treasury and approved by Parliament via legislation.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Additional revenues are paid by the Department for Work and Pensions to compensate for subsidised licences for eligible over-75-year-olds.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The licence fee is classified as a tax, and its evasion is a criminal offence.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Since 1991, collection and enforcement of the licence fee has been the responsibility of the BBC in its role as TV Licensing Authority.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC carries out surveillance (mostly using subcontractors) on properties (under the auspices of the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000) and may conduct searches of a property using a search warrant.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] According to TV Licensing, 216,900 people in the UK were caught watching TV without a licence in 2018/19.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Licence fee evasion makes up about one-tenth of all cases prosecuted in magistrates' courts, representing 0.3% of court time.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Income from commercial enterprises and from overseas sales of its catalogue of programmes has substantially increased over recent years, with BBC Worldwide contributing some £243 million to the BBC's core public service business.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] But the licence fee has attracted criticism.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] It has been argued that in an age of multi-stream, multi-channel availability, an obligation to pay a licence fee is no longer appropriate.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC's use of private sector company Capita to send letters to premises not paying the licence fee has been criticised, especially as there have been cases where such letters have been sent to premises which are up to date with their payments, or do not require a TV licence.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC uses advertising campaigns to inform customers of the requirement to pay the licence fee.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Past campaigns have been criticised by Conservative MP Boris Johnson and former MP Ann Widdecombe for having a threatening nature and language used to scare evaders into paying.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Audio clips and television broadcasts are used to inform listeners of the BBC's comprehensive database.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] There are a number of pressure groups campaigning on the issue of the licence fee.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In 2023, about half a million UK households cancelled their TV licence, driven by shifting viewing habits and financial pressures.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] As a result, the BBC saw a decline in revenue, with the number of households paying the licence fee dropping to 23.9 million.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The majority of the BBC's commercial output comes from its commercial arm BBC Worldwide which sell programmes abroad and exploit key brands for merchandise.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In April 2026, the BBC announced that they would be cutting between 1,800 and 2,000 jobs, citing a need to save £500 million over the coming two years.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Broadcasting House in Portland Place, central London, is the official headquarters of the BBC.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] It is also the home of BBC News, which relocated to the building from BBC Television Centre in 2013.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] On the front of the building are statues of Prospero and Ariel, characters from William Shakespeare's play *The Tempest*, sculpted by Eric Gill.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Renovation of Broadcasting House began in 2002, and was completed in 2012.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Until it closed at the end of March 2013, BBC Television was based at Television Centre, a purpose-built television facility opened in 1960 located in White City, four miles (6 km) west of central London.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] This facility was host to a number of famous guests and programmes through the years, and its name and image is familiar with many British citizens.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Nearby, the White City Place complex contains numerous programme offices, housed in Centre House, the Media Centre and Broadcast Centre.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] It is in this area around Shepherd's Bush that the majority of BBC employees worked.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] As part of a major reorganisation of BBC property, the entire BBC News operation relocated from the News Centre at BBC Television Centre to the refurbished Broadcasting House to create what is being described as "one of the world's largest live broadcast centres".
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC News Channel and BBC News International relocated to the premises in early 2013.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Broadcasting House is now also home to most of the BBC's national radio stations, and the BBC World Service.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The major part of this plan involved the demolition of the two post-war extensions to the building and construction of an extension designed by Sir Richard MacCormac of MJP Architects.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] This move concentrated the BBC's London operations, allowing them to sell Television Centre.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] As well as the two main sites in London (Broadcasting House and White City), there are seven other important BBC production centres in the UK, mainly specialising in different productions.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Cardiff is home to BBC Cymru Wales, which specialises in drama production.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Open since 2012, and containing 7 new studios, Roath Lock is notable as the home of productions such as *Doctor Who* and *Casualty*.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Broadcasting House Belfast, home to BBC Northern Ireland, specialises in original drama and comedy, and has taken part in many co-productions with independent companies and notably with RTÉ in the Republic of Ireland.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC Scotland, based in Pacific Quay, Glasgow is a large producer of programmes for the network, including several quiz shows.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In England, the larger regions also produce some programming.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Previously the largest hub of BBC programming from the regions had been BBC North West.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] At present they produce all religious and ethical programmes on the BBC, as well as other programmes such as *A Question of Sport*.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] However, this is to be merged and expanded under the BBC North project, which involved the region moving from New Broadcasting House, Manchester, to MediaCityUK.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC Midlands, based at Mailbox Birmingham, also produces drama and contains the headquarters for the English regions and the BBC's daytime output.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Other production centres include Broadcasting House Bristol, home of BBC West and famously the BBC Studios Natural History Unit and to a lesser extent, Quarry Hill in Leeds, home of BBC Yorkshire.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] There are also many smaller local and regional studios throughout the UK, operating the BBC regional television services and the BBC Local Radio stations.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC also operates several news gathering centres in various locations around the world, which provide news coverage of that region to the national and international news operations.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In 2004 the BBC contracted out its former BBC Technology division to the German engineering and electronics company Siemens IT Solutions and Services (SIS), outsourcing its IT, telephony and broadcast technology systems.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] When Atos Origin acquired the SIS division from Siemens in December 2010 for €850 million (£720m), the BBC support contract also passed to Atos, and in July 2011, the BBC announced to staff that its technology support would become an Atos service.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Siemens staff working on the BBC contract were transferred to Atos; the BBC's Information Technology systems are now managed by Atos.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In 2012, the BBC's then-chief technology officer John Linwood, expressed confidence in service improvements to the BBC's technology provision brought about by Atos.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] He also stated that supplier accountability had been strengthened following some high-profile technology failures which had taken place during the partnership with Siemens.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC operates several television channels nationally and internationally.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC One and BBC Two are the flagship television channels.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Others include the youth channel BBC Three, cultural and documentary channel BBC Four, the British and international variations of the BBC News channel, parliamentary channel BBC Parliament, and two children's channels, CBBC and CBeebies.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Digital television is now entrenched in the UK, with analogue transmission completely phased out as of December 2012.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC One is a regionalised TV service which provides opt-outs throughout the day for local news and other local programming.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] These variations are more pronounced in the BBC "Nations", i.e.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales, where the presentation is mostly carried out locally on BBC One and Two, and where programme schedules can vary considerably from that of the network.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC Two variations exist in the Nations; however, English regions today rarely have the option to opt out as regional programming now exists only on BBC One.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In 2019, the Scottish variation of BBC Two ceased operation and was replaced with the networked version in favour of a new BBC Scotland channel.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC Two was the first channel to be transmitted on 625 lines, in 1964.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] It then carried a small-scale regular colour service from 1967.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] A new Scottish Gaelic television channel, BBC Alba, was launched in September 2008.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] It is also the first multi-genre channel to come entirely from Scotland with almost all of its programmes made in Scotland.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The service was initially available only via satellite but since June 2011 has been available to viewers in Scotland on Freeview and cable television.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC currently operates HD simulcasts of all its nationwide channels with the exception of BBC Parliament.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Until 26 March 2013, a separate channel called BBC HD was available, in place of BBC Two HD.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] It launched on 15 May 2006, following a 12-month trial of the broadcasts.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] It became a proper channel in 2007, and screened HD programmes as simulcasts of the main network, or as repeats.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The corporation has been producing programmes in the format for many years, and stated that it hoped to produce 100% of new programmes in HDTV by 2010.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] On 3 November 2010, a high-definition simulcast of BBC One was launched, entitled BBC One HD, and BBC Two HD launched on 26 March 2013, replacing BBC HD.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Scotland's new television channel, BBC Scotland, launched in February 2019.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In the Republic of Ireland, Belgium, the Netherlands and Switzerland, the BBC channels are available in a number of ways.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In these countries digital and cable operators carry a range of BBC channels.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Since 1975 the BBC has also provided its TV programmes to the British Forces Broadcasting Service (BFBS), allowing members of UK military serving abroad to watch them on four dedicated TV channels.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] From 27 March 2013, BFBS will carry versions of BBC One and BBC Two, which will include children's programming from CBBC, as well as carrying programming from BBC Three on a new channel called BFBS Extra.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Since 2008 all BBC channels are available to watch online through the BBC iPlayer service.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] This online streaming ability came about following experiments with live streaming, involving streaming certain channels in the UK.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In February 2014, Director-General Tony Hall announced that the corporation needed to save £100 million.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In March 2014, the BBC confirmed plans for BBC Three to become an internet-only channel.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] An earlier ten months of listings are to be obtained from other sources.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] They identified about five million programmes, involving 8.5 million actors, presenters, writers and technical staff.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The Genome project was opened to public access on 15 October 2014, with corrections to OCR errors and changes to advertised schedules being crowdsourced.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC has ten radio stations serving the whole of the UK, a further seven stations in the "national regions" (Wales, Scotland, and Northern Ireland), and 39 other local stations serving defined areas of England.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Of the ten national stations, five are major stations and are available on FM or AM as well as on DAB and online.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In addition to these five stations, the BBC runs a further five stations that broadcast on DAB and online only.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] These stations supplement and expand on the big five stations, and were launched in 2002.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 1Xtra sisters Radio 1, and broadcasts new Black music and urban tracks.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 5 Sports Extra sisters 5 Live and offers extra sport analysis, including broadcasting sports that previously were not covered.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 6 Music offers alternative music genres and is notable as a platform for new artists.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 7, later renamed BBC Radio 4 Extra, provides archive drama, comedy and children's programming.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The final station is the BBC Asian Network, providing music, talk and news to this section of the community.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] This station evolved out of Local radio stations serving certain areas, and as such this station is available on medium wave frequency in some areas of the Midlands.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] As well as the national stations, the BBC also provides 40 BBC Local Radio stations in England and the Channel Islands, each named for and covering a particular city and its surrounding area (e.g.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC Radio Bristol), county or region (e.g.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC Three Counties Radio), or geographical area (e.g.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC Radio Solent covering the central south coast).
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] A further six stations broadcast in what the BBC terms "the national regions": Wales, Scotland, and Northern Ireland.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] These are BBC Radio Wales (in English), BBC Radio Cymru (in Welsh), BBC Radio Scotland (in English), BBC Radio nan Gàidheal (in Scottish Gaelic), BBC Radio Ulster, and BBC Radio Foyle, the latter being an opt-out station from Radio Ulster for the north-west of Northern Ireland.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC's UK national channels are also broadcast in the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man (although these Crown Dependencies are outside the UK), and in the former there are two local stations – BBC Radio Guernsey and BBC Radio Jersey.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] There is no BBC local radio station, however, in the Isle of Man, partly because the island has long been served by the popular independent commercial station, Manx Radio, which predates the existence of BBC Local Radio.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC services in the dependencies are financed from television licence fees which are set at the same level as those payable in the UK, although collected locally.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] This is the subject of some controversy in the Isle of Man since, as well as having no BBC Local Radio service, the island also lacks a local television news service analogous to that provided by BBC Channel Islands.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] It is broadcast worldwide on shortwave radio, DAB and online and has an estimated weekly audience of 192 million, and its websites have an audience of 38 million people per week.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Since 2005, it is also available on DAB in the UK, a step not taken before, due to the way it is funded.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Following the Government's spending review in 2011, the service was funded for the first time through the Licence fee.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In recent years, some services of the World Service have been reduced: the Thai service ended in 2006, as did the Eastern European languages.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Resources were diverted instead into the new BBC News Arabic.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Historically the BBC was the only legal radio broadcaster based in the UK mainland until 1967, when University Radio York, then under the name *Radio York*, was launched as the first, and now oldest, legal independent radio station in the country.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] However, the BBC did not enjoy a complete monopoly before this, as several Continental stations, such as Radio Luxembourg, had broadcast programmes in English to Britain since the 1930s and the Isle of Man-based Manx Radio began in 1964.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Today, despite the advent of commercial broadcasting, BBC radio stations remain among the most listened-to in the country.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Radio 2 has the largest audience share (up to 16.8% in 2011–12) and Radios 1 and 4 ranked second and third in terms of weekly reach.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC programming is also available to other services and in other countries.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Since 1943, the BBC has provided radio programming to the British Forces Broadcasting Service, which broadcasts in countries where British troops are stationed.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 1 is also carried in Canada on SiriusXM (online streaming only).
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC is a patron of the Radio Academy, a registered UK charity that promotes excellence in broadcasting.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC News is the largest broadcast news gathering operation in the world, providing services to BBC domestic radio as well as television networks such as the BBC News, BBC Parliament and BBC News International.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In addition to this, news stories are available on the BBC Red Button service and BBC News Online.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In addition to this, the BBC has been developing new ways to access BBC News and as a result, has launched the service on BBC Mobile, making it accessible to mobile phones and PDAs, as well as developing alerts by email, on digital television, and on computers through a desktop alert.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Ratings figures suggest that during major incidents such as the 7 July 2005 London bombings or royal events, the UK audience overwhelmingly turns to the BBC's coverage as opposed to its commercial rivals.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] On 7 July 2005, the day there were a series of coordinated bomb blasts on London's public transport system, the BBC Online website recorded an all time bandwidth peak of 11 Gb/s at 12.00 on 7 July.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC News received some 1 billion total hits on the day of the event (including all images, text, and HTML), serving some 5.5 terabytes of data.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] At peak times during the day, there were 40,000-page requests per second for the BBC News website.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The previous day's announcement of the 2012 Summer Olympics being awarded to London caused a peak of about 5 Gbit/s.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The previous all-time high at BBC Online was caused by the announcement of the Michael Jackson verdict, which used 7.2 Gbit/s.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC's online presence includes a comprehensive news website and archive.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC's first official online service was the BBC Networking Club, which was launched on 11 May 1994.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The service was subsequently relaunched as BBC Online in 1997, before being renamed BBCi, then bbc.co.uk, before it was rebranded back as BBC Online.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The website is funded by the Licence fee, but uses GeoIP technology, allowing advertisements to be carried on the site when viewed outside of the UK.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC claims the site to be "Europe's most popular content-based site" and states that 13.2 million people in the UK visit the site's more than two million pages each day.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The centre of the website is the Homepage, which features a modular layout.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Users can choose which modules, and which information, is displayed on their homepage, allowing the user to customise it.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] This system was first launched in December 2007, becoming permanent in February 2008, and has undergone a few aesthetical changes since then.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The home page then has links to other micro-sites, such as BBC News Online, Sport, Weather, TV, and Radio.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] As part of the site, every programme on BBC Television or Radio is given its own page, with bigger programmes getting their own micro-site, and as a result it is often common for viewers and listeners to be told URLs for the programme website.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Also, through participation in the Creative Archive Licence group, bbc.co.uk allowed legal downloads of selected archive material via the internet.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC has often included learning as part of its online service, running services such as BBC Jam, Learning Zone Class Clips and also runs services such as BBC WebWise and First Click which are designed to teach people how to use the internet.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC Jam was a free online service, delivered through broadband and narrowband connections, providing high-quality interactive resources designed to stimulate learning at home and at school.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Initial content was made available in January 2006; however, BBC Jam was suspended on 20 March 2007 due to allegations made to the European Commission that it was damaging the interests of the commercial sector of the industry.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In recent years some major on-line companies and politicians have complained that BBC Online receives too much funding from the television licence, meaning that other websites are unable to compete with the vast amount of advertising-free on-line content available on BBC Online.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Some have proposed that the amount of licence fee money spent on BBC Online should be reduced—either being replaced with funding from advertisements or subscriptions, or a reduction in the amount of content available on the site.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In response to this the BBC carried out an investigation, and has now set in motion a plan to change the way it provides its online services.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC Online will now attempt to fill in gaps in the market, and will guide users to other websites for currently existing market provision.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] (For example, instead of providing local events information and timetables, users will be guided to outside websites already providing that information.) Part of this plan included the BBC closing some of its websites, and rediverting money to redevelop other parts.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] On 26 February 2010 *The Times* claimed that Mark Thompson, Director General of the BBC, proposed that the BBC's web output should be cut by 50%, with online staff numbers and budgets reduced by 25% in a bid to scale back BBC operations and allow commercial rivals more room.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] On 2 March 2010, the BBC reported that it would cut its website spending by 25% and close BBC 6 Music and Asian Network, as part of Mark Thompson's plans to make "a smaller, fitter BBC for the digital age".
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC Red Button is the brand name for the BBC's interactive television services, which are available through Freeview (digital terrestrial), as well as Freesat, Sky UK (satellite), and Virgin Media (cable).
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Unlike Ceefax, the service's analogue counterpart, BBC Red Button is able to display full-colour graphics, photographs, and video, as well as programmes and can be accessed from any BBC channel.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The service carries News, Weather and Sport 24 hours a day, but also provides extra features related to programmes specific at that time.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Examples include viewers to play along at home to gameshows, to give, voice and vote on opinions to issues, as used alongside programmes such as *Question Time*.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] At some points in the year, when multiple sporting events occur, some coverage of less mainstream sports or games are frequently placed on the Red Button for viewers to watch.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Frequently, other features are added unrelated to programmes being broadcast at that time, such as the broadcast of the *Doctor Who* animated episode *Dreamland* in November 2009.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] It also buys a selected number of broadcasts from the Ulster Orchestra in Belfast and the BBC Big Band.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC Proms have been produced by the BBC every year since 1927, stepping in to fund the popular eight-week summer classical music festival when music publishers Chappell and Co withdrew their support.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In 1930, the newly formed BBC Symphony Orchestra gave all 49 Proms, and have performed at every Last Night of the Proms since then.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The Proms have been held at the Royal Albert Hall since 1941, and the BBC's orchestras and choirs are the backbone of the festival, giving about 40% to 50% of all performances each season.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Many famous musicians of every genre have played at the BBC, such as The Beatles (*Live at the BBC* is one of their many albums).
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC is also responsible for the broadcast of Glastonbury Festival, Reading and Leeds Festivals and United Kingdom coverage of the Eurovision Song Contest, a show with which the broadcaster has been associated for over 60 years.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC also operates the division of BBC Audiobooks sometimes found in association with Chivers Audiobooks.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC operates other ventures as well as its broadcasting arm.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In addition to broadcasting output on television and radio, some programmes are also displayed on the BBC Big Screens in several central-city locations.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC and the Foreign, Commonwealth and Development Office also jointly run BBC Monitoring, which monitors radio, television, the press and the internet worldwide.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The National Museum of Computing at Bletchley Park uses BBC Micros as part of a scheme to educate school children about computer programming.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In 1951, in conjunction with Oxford University Press, the BBC published *The BBC Hymn Book*, intended to be used by radio listeners to follow hymns being broadcast.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The book was published both with and without music, the music edition being entitled *The BBC Hymn Book with Music*.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC provided the world's first teletext service called Ceefax (near-homophonous with "See Facts") from 23 September 1974 until 23 October 2012 on the BBC1 analogue channel, then later on BBC2.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] It showed informational pages, such as news, sport, and the weather.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] From New Year's Eve, 1974, ITV's Oracle tried to compete with Ceefax.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] During its lifetime, Ceefax attracted millions of viewers, right up until 2012, prior to the digital switchover in the United Kingdom.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Since then, the BBC's Red Button Service has provided a digital information system that replaced Ceefax.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In 2016 the BBC, in partnership with fellow UK broadcasters ITV and Channel 4 (the latter later withdrew from the project), set up 'project kangaroo' to develop an international online streaming service to rival services such as Netflix and Hulu.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] During the development stages 'Britflix' was touted as a potential name.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] However, the service eventually launched as BritBox in March 2017.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The online platform shows a catalogue of classic BBC and ITV shows, as well as making a number of programmes available shortly after their UK broadcast.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] As of 2021, BritBox is available in the UK, the US, Canada, Australia, and, more recently, South Africa, with the potential availability for new markets in the future.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC Studios is the wholly owned commercial subsidiary of the BBC, responsible for the commercial exploitation of BBC programmes and other properties, including a number of television stations throughout the world.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] It was formed in 2018 after the merger of the BBC's commercial production arm and the BBC's commercial international distribution arm, BBC Worldwide, with the latter formed in 1995 following the restructuring of its predecessor, BBC Enterprises.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Prior to this, the selling of BBC television programmes was at first handled in 1958 with the establishment of a business manager post.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] This expanded until the establishment of the Television Promotions (renamed Television Enterprises) department in 1960 under a general manager.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The company owns and administers a number of commercial stations around the world operating in a number of territories and on a number of different platforms.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] These include BBC UKTV for the Australasia region, and formerly BBC America (now fully owned by AMC Networks).
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The company airs two channels aimed at children, an international CBeebies channel and BBC Kids, a joint venture with Knowledge Network Corporation.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The company also runs BBC Earth, which distributes the BBC's natural history content to countries outside the UK, and BBC Lifestyle, broadcasting programmes based on themes of Food, Style and Wellbeing.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In addition to this, BBC Studios ran an international version of the channel BBC HD.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC Studios also distributes the 24-hour international news channel BBC News.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The station is separate from BBC Studios to maintain the station's neutral point of view, but is distributed by BBC Studios.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The channel itself is the oldest surviving entity of its kind, and has 50 foreign news bureaus and correspondents in nearly all countries in the world.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] As officially surveyed, it is available to more than 294 million households, significantly more than CNN's estimated 200 million.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In addition to these international channels, BBC Studios also owns the UKTV network of seven channels.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] These channels contain BBC archive programming to be rebroadcast on their respective channels: Alibi, crime dramas; Dave (slogan: "The Home of Witty Banter"); Drama, drama, launched in 2013; Eden, nature; Gold, comedy; W, Entertainment; and Yesterday, history programming.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In addition to these channels, many BBC programmes are sold via BBC Studios to foreign television stations with comedy, documentaries, crime dramas (such as *Luther* and *Peaky Blinders*) and historical drama productions being the most popular.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC's most successful reality television show format, *Strictly Come Dancing*—under the title *Dancing with the Stars*—has been exported to 60 other countries.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Shows commissioned and distributed by the BBC include the *Wallace & Gromit* animated comedy short films *The Wrong Trousers* and *A Close Shave*.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC television news also appears nightly on many PBS stations in the US, as do reruns of BBC programmes such as *EastEnders*, and in New Zealand on TVNZ 1.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In addition to programming, BBC Studios produces material to accompany programmes.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The company maintained the publishing arm of the BBC, BBC Magazines, which published the *Radio Times*; first published by the BBC on 28 September 1923, it is the world's first broadcast listings magazine.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] *Radio Times* covers all British television and radio programming schedules, and the 1988 Christmas edition sold 11,220,666 copies, which the *Guinness World Records* certified as the biggest-selling edition of any British magazine in history.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Other magazines that support BBC programming include *BBC Top Gear*, *BBC Good Food*, *BBC Sky at Night*, *BBC History*, *BBC Wildlife* and *BBC Music*.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC Magazines was sold to Exponent Private Equity in 2011, which merged it with Origin Publishing (previously owned by BBC Worldwide between 2004 and 2006) to form Immediate Media Company.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] BBC Studios also publishes books, to accompany programmes such as *Sherlock* and *Doctor Who* under the BBC Books brand, a publishing imprint majority owned by Random House.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Archive programming and classical music recordings are sold under the brand BBC Legends.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Until the development, popularisation, and domination of television, radio was the broadcast medium upon which people in the United Kingdom relied.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] It "reached into every home in the land, and simultaneously united the nation, an important factor during the Second World War".
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC introduced the world's first "high-definition" 405-line television service in 1936.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] It suspended its television service during the Second World War and until 1946, but remained the only television broadcaster in the UK until 1955, when Independent Television (ITV) began operating.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] This heralded the transformation of television into a popular and dominant medium.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Nevertheless, "throughout the 1950s radio still remained the dominant source of broadcast comedy".
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Further, the BBC was the only legal radio broadcaster until 1968 (when University Radio York obtained its first licence).
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Despite the advent of commercial television and radio, with competition from ITV, Channel 4 and Sky, the BBC has remained one of the main elements in British popular culture through its obligation to produce TV and radio programmes for mass audiences.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] However, the arrival of BBC2 allowed the BBC also to make programmes for minority interests in drama, documentaries, current affairs, entertainment, and sport.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Described as television's first "watercooler moment" by *The Telegraph*, the BBC's 1954 adaptation of *Nineteen Eighty-Four* made a dramatic impact on a fledgling television audience who were horrified by the graphic depiction of a totalitarian regime controlling the population.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Making his BBC debut in 1949, Benny Hill with *The Benny Hill Show* became the first British comedian to become famous via television.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Popular comedy duos on the BBC include Morecambe and Wise (whose show debuted in 1968) and The Two Ronnies (debuting in 1971).
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Black comedy sitcom *Blackadder*, starring Rowan Atkinson as the title character, ran for four series between 1983 and 1989.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The British Academy Film Awards (BAFTAs) was first broadcast on the BBC in 1956, with Vivien Leigh as the host.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The television equivalent, the British Academy Television Awards, has been screened exclusively on the BBC since a 2007 awards ceremony that included wins for Jim Broadbent (Best actor) and Ricky Gervais (Best comedy performance).
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The term "BBC English" was used as an alternative name for Received Pronunciation, and the *English Pronouncing Dictionary* uses the term "BBC Pronunciation" to label its recommendations.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] However, the BBC itself now makes more use of regional accents to reflect the diversity of the UK, while continuing to expect clarity and fluency of its presenters.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] From its "starchy" beginnings, the BBC has also become more inclusive, and now attempts to accommodate the interests of all strata of society and all minorities, because they all pay the licence fee.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Older domestic UK audiences often refer to the BBC as "the Beeb", a nickname coined by Peter Sellers during a 1972 reunion of the 1950s BBC radio comedy *The Goon Show*, when he referred to the "Beeb Beeb Ceeb".
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] It was then shortened and popularised by radio DJ Kenny Everett.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] David Bowie's recording sessions at the BBC were released as *Bowie at the Beeb*, while Queen's BBC recording sessions were released as *At the Beeb*.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The term "Auntie" for the BBC is often credited to radio disc-jockey Jack Jackson.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] To celebrate the fiftieth anniversary of the BBC the song "Auntie" was released in 1972.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] It also featured in the title of the BBC's blooper show, *Auntie's Bloomers*, which was presented by Terry Wogan from 1991 to 2001.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The two nicknames have also been used together as "Auntie Beeb".
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Throughout its existence the BBC has faced numerous accusations regarding many topics: the Iraq war, the Gaza war, politics, ethics and religion, as well as funding and staffing.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] It also has been involved in numerous controversies because of its coverage of specific news stories and programming.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC has been accused repeatedly of anti-Israel bias, and to a greater extent anti-Israel Defense Force bias.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC has long faced accusations of liberal and left-wing bias.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Accusations of a bias against the Premiership of Margaret Thatcher and the Conservative Party were often made against the BBC by members of that government, with Margaret Thatcher herself considering the broadcaster's news coverage to be biased and irresponsible.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In 2011, Peter Sissons, a main news presenter at the BBC from 1989 to 2009, said that "at the core of the BBC, in its very DNA, is a way of thinking that is firmly of the Left".
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Another BBC presenter, Andrew Marr, commented that "the BBC is not impartial or neutral.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] It has a liberal bias, not so much a party-political bias.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] It is better expressed as a cultural liberal bias." Former BBC director Roger Mosey classified it as "liberal defensive".
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In 2022, the BBC chairman, Richard Sharp, said that the BBC "does have a liberal bias" and that the institution is "fighting against it".
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In November 2025, allegations by *The Daily Telegraph* that the BBC had deceptively spliced a Donald Trump speech preceding the January 6 United States Capitol attack in a documentary led to several BBC executives resigning, including the head of the BBC.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Writing for *The Guardian* in 2018, the left-wing columnist Owen Jones stated "the truth is the BBC is stacked full of rightwingers," and cited as an example of bias its employment of "ultra-Thatcherite" Andrew Neil as a politics presenter.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] In November 2025, LibDem leader Ed Davey called for Gibb's removal from the BBC board because of Gibb's alleged role in the 2025 BBC editorial bias controversy.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] A 2018 opinion poll by BMG Research found that 40% of the British public thought that the BBC was politically partisan, with a nearly even split between those who believed it leaned to the left or right.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Additionally oft-cited are its policy of "balancing" appearances by transgender people with activists from gender-critical groups, its manual of style which requires any allegations of transphobia to be challenged by the news presenter, and its policy against using the term "cisgender".
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] The BBC has also been accused by gender-critical groups and BBC staff of having a pro-trans bias, primarily for "failing to make it clear that transgender women are biological males".
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Such accusations have alleged that the BBC's LGBT desk has been "captured by a small group of people" intent on promoting a pro-trans agenda.
[src:arkive/bbc-p02] Shortly thereafter, the BBC began running articles referring to trans women as "biological males who identify as women".
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] A **biodiversity action plan** (**BAP**) is an internationally recognized program aimed at protecting and restoring threatened species and habitats, and at strengthening the resilience of biological systems.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] The concept emerged from the 1992 Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD), which called on participating nations to develop strategies for conserving biodiversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] As of 2009, 191 countries had ratified the CBD, although only a portion of them had produced comprehensive BAP documents.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] A fundamental method of engagement to a BAP is thorough documentation regarding individual species, with emphasis upon the population distribution and conservation status.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] This task, while fundamental, is highly daunting, since only an estimated ten percent of the world's species are believed to have been characterized as of 2006, most of these unknowns being fungi, invertebrate animals, micro-organisms and plants.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] For many bird, mammal and reptile species, information is often available in published literature; however, for fungi, invertebrate animals, micro-organisms and many plants, such information may require considerable local data collection.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] It is also useful to compile time trends of population estimates in order to understand the dynamics of population variability and vulnerability.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] In some parts of the world complete species inventories are not realistic; for example, in the Madagascar dry deciduous forests, many species are completely undocumented and much of the region has never even been systematically explored by scientists.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] A species plan component of a country's BAP should ideally entail a thorough description of the range, habitat, behaviour, breeding and interaction with other species.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Once a determination has been made of conservation status (e.g. rare, endangered, threatened, vulnerable), a plan can then be created to conserve and restore the species population to target levels.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] The plan should also articulate which public and private agencies should implement the protection strategy and indicate budgets available to execute this strategy.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Agricultural practices can reduce the biodiversity of a region significantly.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Biodiversity Action Plans for agricultural production are necessary to ensure a biodiversity friendly production.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] It has not been common for companies to integrate biodiversity aspects into their value chain, but some companies and organizations have shown overall efforts for implementing better practices.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] An existing example for guidelines on biodiversity practices in agriculture is the Biodiversity Action Plan for spice production in India.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] By planning and implementing biodiversity friendly measures, farmers can mitigate negative impacts and support positive influences.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Where a number of threatened species depend upon a specific habitat, it may be appropriate to prepare a habitat protection element of the Biodiversity Action Plan.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Examples of such special habitats are: raised acidic bogs of Scotland; Waterberg Biosphere bushveld in South Africa; California's coastal wetlands; and Sweden's Stora Alvaret on the island of Öland.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] In this case also, careful inventories of species and also the geographic extent and quality of the habitat must be documented.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Then, as with species plans, a program can be created to protect, enhance and/or restore habitat using similar strategies as discussed above under the species plans.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Some examples of individual countries which have produced substantive Biodiversity Action Plans follow.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] In every example the plans concentrate on plants and vertebrate animals, with very little attention to neglected groups such as fungi, invertebrate animals and micro-organisms, even though these are also part of biodiversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Preparation of a country BAP may cost up to 100 million pounds sterling, with annual maintenance costs roughly ten percent of the initial cost.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] If plans took into account neglected groups, the cost would be higher.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Obviously costs for countries with small geographical area or simplified ecosystems have a much lesser cost.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Lucia BAP has been costed in the area of several million pounds sterling.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Australia has developed a detailed and rigorous Biodiversity Action Plan.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] This document estimates that the total number of indigenous species may be 560,000, many of which are endemic.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] A key element of the BAP is protection of the Great Barrier Reef, which is actually in a much higher state of health than most of the world's reefs, Australia having one of the highest percentages of treated wastewater.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] There are however serious ongoing concerns, particularly in regards to the ongoing negative impact on water quality from land use practices.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Also, climate change impact is feared to be significant.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Considerable analysis has been conducted on the sustainable yield of firewood production, a major threat to deforestation in most tropical countries.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Biological inventory work; assessment of harvesting practices; and computer modeling of the dynamics of treefall, rot and harvest; have been carried out to adduce data on safe harvesting rates.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Extensive research has also been conducted on the relation of brush clearance to biodiversity decline and impact on water tables; for example, these effects have been analyzed in the Toolibin Lake wetlands region.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] New Zealand has ratified the Convention on Biological Diversity and as part of The New Zealand Biodiversity Strategy and Biodiversity Action Plans are implemented on ten separate themes.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Local government and some companies also have their own Biodiversity Action Plan.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Lucia BAP recognizes impacts of large numbers of tourists to the marine and coastal diversity of the Soufrière area of the country.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] The BAP specifically acknowledges that the carrying capacity for human use and water pollution discharge of sensitive reef areas was exceeded by the year 1990.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] The plan also addresses conservation of the historic island fishing industry.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] In 1992, several institutions in conjunction with native fishermen to produce a sustainable management plan for fishery resources, embodied in the Soufrière Marine Management Area.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Lucia BAP features significant involvement from the University of the West Indies.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Specific detailed attention is given to three species of threatened marine turtles, to a variety of vulnerable birds and a number of pelagic fishes and cetaceans.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] In terms of habitat conservation the plan focusses attention on the biologically productive mangrove swamps and notes that virtually all mangrove areas had already come under national protection by 1984.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] The Tanzania national BAP addresses issues related to sustainable use of Lake Manyara, an extensive freshwater lake, whose usage by humans accelerated in the period 1950 to 1990.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] The designation of the Lake Manyara Biosphere Reserve under UNESCO's Man and the Biosphere Programme in 1981 combines conservation of the lake and surrounding high value forests with sustainable use of the wetlands area and simple agriculture.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] This BAP has united principal lake users in establishing management targets.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] The biosphere reserve has induced sustainable management of the wetlands, including monitoring groundwater and the chemistry of the escarpment water source.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] The United Kingdom Biodiversity Action Plan covers not only terrestrial species associated with lands within the UK, but also marine species and migratory birds, which spend a limited time in the UK or its offshore waters.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] The UK plan encompasses "391 Species Action Plans, 45 Habitat Action Plans and 162 Local Biodiversity Action Plans with targeted actions".
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] This plan is noteworthy because of its extensive detail, clarity of endangerment mechanisms, specificity of actions, follow up monitoring program and its inclusion of migrating cetaceans and pelagic birds.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] On August 28, 2007, the new Biodiversity Action Plan (BAP) [launched in 1997] identified 1,149 species and 65 habitats in the UK that needed conservation and greater protection.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] The updated list included the hedgehog, house sparrow, grass snake and the garden tiger moth, while otters, bottlenose dolphins and red squirrels remained in need of habitat protection.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] In May 2011, the European Commission adopted a new strategy to halt the loss of biodiversity and ecosystem services in the EU by 2020, in line with the commitments made at the 10th meeting of the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) held in Nagoya, Japan in 2010.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] In 2012 the UK BAP was succeeded by the 'UK Post-2010 Biodiversity Framework'.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] To support the work of the UK BAP, the UK BAP website was created by JNCC in 2001.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] The website contained information on the BAP process, hosted all relevant documents, and provided news and relevant updates.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] In March 2011, as part of the UK government's review of websites, the UK BAP site was ‘closed’, and the core content was migrated into the JNCC website.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Content from the original UK BAP website has been archived by the National Archives as snapshots from various dates (for example, UK *BAP*: copy March 2011; copy 2012).
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Twenty-six years prior to the international biodiversity convention, the United States had launched a national program to protect threatened species in the form of the 1966 Endangered Species Act.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] The legislation created broad authority for analyzing and listing species of concern, and mandated that Species Recovery Plans be created.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Thus, while the USA is an unratified signer of the accord, arguably it has the longest track record and most comprehensive program of species protection of any country.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] There are about 7000 listed species (e.g. endangered or threatened), of which about half have approved Recovery Plans.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] While this number of species seems high compared to other countries, the value is rather indicative of the total number of species characterized, which is extremely large.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Five major divisions of habitat have been identified in Uzbekistan’s BAP: Wetlands (including reed habitat and man-made marsh); desert ecosystems (including sandy, stony and clay); steppes; riparian ecosystems; and mountain ecosystems.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Over 27,000 species have been inventoried in the country, with a high rate of endemism for fishes and reptiles.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Principal threats to biodiversity are related to human activities associated with overpopulation and generally related to agricultural intensification.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Major geographic regions encompassed by the BAP include the Aral Sea Programme (threatened by long-term drainage and salination, largely for cotton production), the Nuratau Biosphere Reserve, and the Western Tien Shan Mountains Programme (in conjunction with Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan).
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Some developing countries criticize the emphasis of BAPs, because these plans inherently favour consideration of wildlife protection above food and industrial production, and in some cases may represent an obstacle to population growth.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] The plans are costly to produce, a fact which makes it difficult for many smaller countries and poorer countries to comply.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] In terms of the plans themselves, many countries have adopted pro-forma plans including little research and even less in the way of natural resource management.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Almost universally, this has resulted in plans which emphasize plants and vertebrate animals, and which overlook fungi, invertebrate animals and micro-organisms.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] With regard to specific world regions, there is a notable lack of substantive participation by most of the Middle Eastern countries and much of Africa, the latter of which may be impeded by economic considerations of plan preparation.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Some governments such as the European Union have diverted the purpose of a biodiversity action plan, and implemented the convention accord by a set of economic development policies with referencing certain ecosystems' protection.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] The definition of biodiversity under the Convention on Biological Diversity now recognises that biodiversity is a combination of ecosystem structure and function, as much as its components e.g. species, habitats and genetic resources.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Biodiversity and wildlife are not the same thing.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] The traditional focus on threatened species in BAPs is at odds with the principles of biodiversity management because, by the time species become threatened, the processes that maintain biodiversity are already compromised.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Individual species are also regarded as generally poor indicators of biodiversity when it comes to actual planning.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] A species approach to BAPs only serves to identify and at best, apply a patch to existing problems.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Increasingly, biodiversity planners are looking through the lens of ecosystem services.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Critics of biodiversity are often confusing the need to protect species (their intrinsic value) with the need to maintain ecosystem processes, which ultimately maintain human society and do not compromise economic development.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Hence, a core principle of biodiversity management, that traditional BAPs overlook, is the need to incorporate cultural, social and economic values in the process.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Modern day BAPs use an analysis of ecosystem services, key ecological process drivers, and use species as one of many indicators of change.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] They would seek to maintain structure and function by addressing habitat connectivity and resilience and may look at communities of species (threatened or otherwise) as one method of monitoring outcomes.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Ultimately, species are the litmus test for biodiversity – viable populations of species can only be expected to exist in relatively intact habitats.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] However, the rationale behind BAPs is to "conserve and restore" biodiversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] One of the fastest developing areas of management is biodiversity offsets.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] The principles are in keeping with ecological impact assessment, which in turn depends on good quality BAPs for evaluation.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-action-plan] Contemporary principles of biodiversity management, such as those produced by the Business Biodiversity Offsets Program are now integral to any plans to manage biodiversity, including the development of BAPs.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Since life began on Earth, six major mass extinctions and several minor events have led to large and sudden drops in biodiversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The Phanerozoic aeon (the last 540 million years) marked a rapid growth in biodiversity via the Cambrian explosion.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] In this period, the majority of multicellular phyla first appeared.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The next 400 million years included repeated, massive biodiversity losses.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Those events have been classified as mass extinction events.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] In the Carboniferous, rainforest collapse may have led to a great loss of plant and animal life.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The Permian–Triassic extinction event, 251 million years ago, was the worst; vertebrate recovery took 30 million years.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Human activities have led to an ongoing biodiversity loss and an accompanying loss of genetic diversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] This process is often referred to as Holocene extinction, or the *sixth mass extinction*.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] For example, it was estimated in 2007 that up to 30% of all species will be extinct by 2050.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Destroying habitats for farming is a key reason why biodiversity is decreasing today.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] This can be seen for example in the effects of climate change on biomes.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] This anthropogenic extinction may have started toward the end of the Pleistocene, as some studies suggest that the megafaunal extinction event that took place around the end of the last ice age partly resulted from overhunting.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Biologists most often define *biodiversity* as the "totality of genes, species and ecosystems of a region".
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] (2011), there are approximately 8.7 million terrestrial species and 2.2 million oceanic species.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The authors note that these estimates are strongest for eukaryotic organisms and likely represent the lower bound of prokaryotic diversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Since the rate of extinction has increased, many extant species may become extinct before they are described.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Not surprisingly, in the Animalia the most studied groups are birds and mammals, whereas fishes and arthropods are the least studied animal groups.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] During the last century, decreases in biodiversity have been increasingly observed.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] It was estimated in 2007 that up to 30% of all species will be extinct by 2050.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Of these, about one eighth of known plant species are threatened with extinction.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Estimates reach as high as 140,000 species per year (based on Species-area theory).
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] This figure indicates unsustainable ecological practices, because few species emerge each year.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The rate of species loss is greater now than at any time in human history, with extinctions occurring at rates hundreds of times higher than background extinction rates. and expected to still grow in the upcoming years.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] As of 2012, some studies suggest that 25% of all mammal species could be extinct in 20 years.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] According to a 2016 study by the World Wildlife Fund, population abundance among 3,706 monitored vertebrate species is exhibiting a persistent downward trend.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The *Living Planet Report 2014* claims that "the number of mammals, birds, reptiles, amphibians, and fish across the globe is, on average, about half the size it was 40 years ago".
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Of that number, 39% accounts for the terrestrial wildlife gone, 39% for the marine wildlife gone and 76% for the freshwater wildlife gone.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity took the biggest hit in Latin America, plummeting 83 percent.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] High-income countries showed a 10% increase in biodiversity, which was canceled out by a loss in low-income countries.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] This is despite the fact that high-income countries use five times the ecological resources of low-income countries, which was explained as a result of a process whereby wealthy nations are outsourcing resource depletion to poorer nations, which are suffering the greatest ecosystem losses.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] A 2017 study published in *PLOS One* found that the biomass of insect life in Germany had declined by three-quarters in the last 25 years.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Dave Goulson of Sussex University stated that their study suggested that humans "appear to be making vast tracts of land inhospitable to most forms of life, and are currently on course for ecological Armageddon.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] In 2020 the World Wildlife Fund published a report saying that "biodiversity is being destroyed at a rate unprecedented in human history".
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The report claims that 68% of the population of the examined species were destroyed in the years 1970 – 2016.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Of 70,000 monitored species, around 48% are experiencing population declines from human activity (in 2023), whereas only 3% have increasing populations.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Rates of decline in biodiversity in the current sixth mass extinction match or exceed rates of loss in the five previous mass extinction events in the fossil record.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity loss is in fact "one of the most critical manifestations of the Anthropocene" (since around the 1950s); the continued decline of biodiversity constitutes "an unprecedented threat" to the continued existence of human civilization.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The reduction is caused primarily by human impacts, particularly habitat destruction.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Since the Stone Age, species loss has accelerated above the average basal rate, driven by human activity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Estimates of species losses are at a rate 100–10,000 times as fast as is typical in the fossil record.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Loss of biodiversity results in the loss of natural capital that supplies ecosystem goods and services.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Species today are being wiped out at a rate 100 to 1,000 times higher than baseline, and the rate of extinctions is increasing.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] This process destroys the resilience and adaptability of life on Earth.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] In 2006, many species were formally classified as rare or endangered or threatened; moreover, scientists have estimated that millions more species are at risk which have not been formally recognized.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] About 40 percent of the 40,177 species assessed using the IUCN Red List criteria are now listed as threatened with extinction—a total of 16,119.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] As of late 2022 9251 species were considered part of the IUCN's critically endangered.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Numerous scientists and the IPBES *Global Assessment Report on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services* assert that human population growth and overconsumption are the primary factors in this decline.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] However, other scientists have criticized this finding and say that loss of habitat caused by "the growth of commodities for export" is the main driver.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] A 2025 study found that human activities are responsible for biodiversity loss across all species and ecosystems.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Climate change is an important driver of global biodiversity loss because of its impacts on ecosystems.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] At the same time, biodiversity and climate are closely interconnected, as biodiversity influences the mitigation and adaptation potential of ecosystems.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] For more information on these interactions, see the 'Regulating services' section below.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Other studies, however, have pointed out that habitat destruction for the expansion of agriculture and the overexploitation of wildlife are the more significant drivers of contemporary biodiversity loss, not climate change.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is not evenly distributed, rather it varies greatly across the globe as well as within regions and seasons.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Among other factors, the diversity of all living things (biota) depends on temperature, precipitation, altitude, soils, geography and the interactions between other species.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The study of the spatial distribution of organisms, species and ecosystems, is the science of biogeography.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Diversity consistently measures higher in the tropics and in other localized regions such as the Cape Floristic Region and lower in polar regions generally.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Rain forests that have had wet climates for a long time, such as Yasuní National Park in Ecuador, have particularly high biodiversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] There is local biodiversity, which directly impacts daily life, affecting the availability of fresh water, food choices, and fuel sources for humans.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Regional biodiversity includes habitats and ecosystems that synergizes and either overlaps or differs on a regional scale.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] National biodiversity within a country determines the ability for a country to thrive according to its habitats and ecosystems on a national scale.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Also, within a country, endangered species are initially supported on a national level then internationally.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Ecotourism may be utilized to support the economy and encourages tourists to continue to visit and support species and ecosystems they visit, while they enjoy the available amenities provided.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] International biodiversity impacts global livelihood, food systems, and health.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Problematic pollution, over consumption, and climate change can devastate international biodiversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Nature-based solutions are a critical tool for a global resolution.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Many species are in danger of becoming extinct and need world leaders to be proactive with the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Terrestrial biodiversity is thought to be up to 25 times greater than ocean biodiversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Forests harbour most of Earth's terrestrial biodiversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The conservation of the world's biodiversity is thus utterly dependent on the way in which we interact with and use the world's forests.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] A new method used in 2011, put the total number of species on Earth at 8.7 million, of which 2.1 million were estimated to live in the ocean.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] However, this estimate seems to under-represent the diversity of microorganisms.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Forests provide habitats for 80 percent of amphibian species, 75 percent of bird species and 68 percent of mammal species.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] About 60 percent of all vascular plants are found in tropical forests.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Mangroves provide breeding grounds and nurseries for numerous species of fish and shellfish and help trap sediments that might otherwise adversely affect seagrass beds and coral reefs, which are habitats for many more marine species.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Forests span around 4 billion acres (nearly a third of the Earth's land mass) and are home to approximately 80% of the world's biodiversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] About 1 billion hectares are covered by primary forests.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Over 700 million hectares of the world's woods are officially protected.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The biodiversity of forests varies considerably according to factors such as forest type, geography, climate and soils – in addition to human use.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Areas with dense human populations and intense agricultural land use, such as Europe, parts of Bangladesh, China, India and North America, are less intact in terms of their biodiversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Northern Africa, southern Australia, coastal Brazil, Madagascar and South Africa, are also identified as areas with striking losses in biodiversity intactness.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] European forests in EU and non-EU nations comprise more than 30% of Europe's land mass (around 227 million hectares), representing an almost 10% growth since 1990.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Generally, there is an increase in biodiversity from the poles to the tropics.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Thus localities at lower latitudes have more species than localities at higher latitudes.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] This is often referred to as the latitudinal gradient in species diversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Several ecological factors may contribute to the gradient, but the ultimate factor behind many of them is the greater mean temperature at the equator compared to that at the poles.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Even though terrestrial biodiversity declines from the equator to the poles, some studies claim that this characteristic is unverified in aquatic ecosystems, especially in marine ecosystems.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The latitudinal distribution of parasites does not appear to follow this rule.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Also, in terrestrial ecosystems the soil bacterial diversity has been shown to be highest in temperate climatic zones, and has been attributed to carbon inputs and habitat connectivity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] In 2016, an alternative hypothesis ("the fractal biodiversity") was proposed to explain the biodiversity latitudinal gradient.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] In this study, the species pool size and the fractal nature of ecosystems were combined to clarify some general patterns of this gradient.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] This hypothesis considers temperature, moisture, and net primary production (NPP) as the main variables of an ecosystem niche and as the axis of the ecological hypervolume.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] In this way, it is possible to build fractal hyper volumes, whose fractal dimension rises to three moving towards the equator.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] A biodiversity hotspot is a region with a high level of endemic species that have experienced great habitat loss.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The term hotspot was introduced in 1988 by Norman Myers.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] While hotspots are spread all over the world, the majority are forest areas and most are located in the tropics.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Brazil's Atlantic Forest is considered one such hotspot, containing roughly 20,000 plant species, 1,350 vertebrates and millions of insects, about half of which occur nowhere else.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The island of Madagascar and India are also particularly notable.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Colombia is characterized by high biodiversity, with the highest rate of species by area unit worldwide and it has the largest number of endemics (species that are not found naturally anywhere else) of any country.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] About 10% of the species of the Earth can be found in Colombia, including over 1,900 species of bird, more than in Europe and North America combined, Colombia has 10% of the world's mammals species, 14% of the amphibian species and 18% of the bird species of the world.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Madagascar dry deciduous forests and lowland rainforests possess a high ratio of endemism.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Since the island separated from mainland Africa 66 million years ago, many species and ecosystems have evolved independently.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Indonesia's 17,000 islands cover 735,355 square miles (1,904,560 km2) and contain 10% of the world's flowering plants, 12% of mammals and 17% of reptiles, amphibians and birds—along with nearly 240 million people.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Many regions of high biodiversity and/or endemism arise from specialized habitats which require unusual adaptations, for example, alpine environments in high mountains, or Northern European peat bogs.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Accurately measuring differences in biodiversity can be difficult.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Selection bias amongst researchers may contribute to biased empirical research for modern estimates of biodiversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is the result of 3.5 billion years of evolution.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The origin of life has not been established by science, however, some evidence suggests that life may already have been well-established only a few hundred million years after the formation of the Earth.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Until approximately 2.5 billion years ago, all life consisted of microorganisms – archaea, bacteria, and single-celled protozoans and protists.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity grew fast during the Phanerozoic (the last 540 million years), especially during the so-called Cambrian explosion—a period during which nearly every phylum of multicellular organisms first appeared.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] However, recent studies suggest that this diversification had started earlier, at least in the Ediacaran, and that it continued in the Ordovician.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Over the next 400 million years or so, invertebrate diversity showed little overall trend and vertebrate diversity shows an overall exponential trend.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] This dramatic rise in diversity was marked by periodic, massive losses of diversity classified as mass extinction events.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The worst was the Permian-Triassic extinction event, 251 million years ago.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Vertebrates took 30 million years to recover from this event.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The most recent major mass extinction event, the Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event, occurred 66 million years ago.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] This period has attracted more attention than others because it resulted in the extinction of the non-avian dinosaurs, which were represented by many lineages at the end of the Maastrichtian, just before that extinction event.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] However, many other taxa were affected by this crisis, which affected even marine taxa, such as ammonites, which also became extinct around that time.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The biodiversity of the past is called Paleobiodiversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The fossil record suggests that the last few million years featured the greatest biodiversity in history.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] However, not all scientists support this view, since there is uncertainty as to how strongly the fossil record is biased by the greater availability and preservation of recent geologic sections.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Some scientists believe that corrected for sampling artifacts, modern biodiversity may not be much different from biodiversity 300 million years ago, whereas others consider the fossil record reasonably reflective of the diversification of life.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Estimates of the present global macroscopic species diversity vary from 2 million to 100 million, with a best estimate of somewhere near 9 million, the vast majority arthropods.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Diversity appears to increase continually in the absence of natural selection.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The existence of a *global carrying capacity*, limiting the amount of life that can live at once, is debated, as is the question of whether such a limit would also cap the number of species.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] While records of life in the sea show a logistic pattern of growth, life on land (insects, plants and tetrapods) shows an exponential rise in diversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] It also appears that the diversity continues to increase over time, especially after mass extinctions.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] On the other hand, changes through the Phanerozoic correlate much better with the hyperbolic model (widely used in population biology, demography and macrosociology, as well as fossil biodiversity) than with exponential and logistic models.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The latter models imply that changes in diversity are guided by a first-order positive feedback (more ancestors, more descendants) and/or a negative feedback arising from resource limitation.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Hyperbolic model implies a second-order positive feedback.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Differences in the strength of the second-order feedback due to different intensities of interspecific competition might explain the faster rediversification of ammonoids in comparison to bivalves after the end-Permian extinction.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The hyperbolic pattern of the world population growth arises from a second-order positive feedback between the population size and the rate of technological growth.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The hyperbolic character of biodiversity growth can be similarly accounted for by a feedback between diversity and community structure complexity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The similarity between the curves of biodiversity and human population probably comes from the fact that both are derived from the interference of the hyperbolic trend with cyclical and stochastic dynamics.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Most biologists agree however that the period since human emergence is part of a new mass extinction, named the Holocene extinction event, caused primarily by the impact humans are having on the environment.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] It has been argued that the present rate of extinction is sufficient to eliminate most species on the planet Earth within 100 years.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] New species are regularly discovered (on average between 5–10,000 new species each year, most of them insects) and many, though discovered, are not yet classified (estimates are that nearly 90% of all arthropods are not yet classified).
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Most of the terrestrial diversity is found in tropical forests and in general, the land has more species than the ocean; some 8.7 million species may exist on Earth, of which some 2.1 million live in the ocean.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] It is estimated that 5 to 50 billion species have existed on the planet.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Assuming that there may be a maximum of about 50 million species currently alive, it stands to reason that greater than 99% of the planet's species went extinct prior to the evolution of humans.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Estimates on the number of Earth's current species range from 10 million to 14 million, of which about 1.2 million have been documented and over 86% have not yet been described.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] However, a May 2016 scientific report estimates that 1 trillion species are currently on Earth, with only one-thousandth of one percent described.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The total amount of related DNA base pairs on Earth is estimated at 5.0 × 1037 and weighs 50 billion tonnes.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] In comparison, the total mass of the biosphere has been estimated to be as much as four trillion tons of carbon.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] In July 2016, scientists reported identifying a set of 355 genes from the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all organisms living on Earth.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The age of Earth is about 4.54 billion years.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The earliest undisputed evidence of life dates at least from 3.7 billion years ago, during the Eoarchean era after a geological crust started to solidify following the earlier molten Hadean eon.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] There are microbial mat fossils found in 3.48 billion-year-old sandstone discovered in Western Australia.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Other early physical evidence of a biogenic substance is graphite in 3.7 billion-year-old meta-sedimentary rocks discovered in Western Greenland.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] More recently, in 2015, "remains of biotic life" were found in 4.1 billion-year-old rocks in Western Australia.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] There have been many claims about biodiversity's effect on the ecosystem services, especially *provisioning* and *regulating services*.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Some of those claims have been validated, some are incorrect and some lack enough evidence to draw definitive conclusions.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Experiments with controlled environments have shown that humans cannot easily build ecosystems to support human needs; for example insect pollination cannot be mimicked, though there have been attempts to create artificial pollinators using unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The economic activity of pollination alone represented between $2.1–14.6 billion in 2003.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Other sources have reported somewhat conflicting results and in 1997 Robert Costanza and his colleagues reported the estimated global value of ecosystem services (not captured in traditional markets) at an average of $33 trillion annually.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity plays a role in multiple ecological regulating services that strengthen the stability, functioning and adaptability of ecosystems.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] For example, plant species richness can increase functional diversity in many ecosystems.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Different plant organisms living together can perform complementary roles such as nutrient cycling and water regulation, which can contribute to the stabilisation of ecosystem processes under climate stress, a mechanism known as niche complementarity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] This could include enhanced transpiration and soil moisture regulation, as more efficient water use can be promoted by the variety of different leaf traits and root depths, which in turn can reduce drought stress and mitigate heat impact.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Climate change is also associated with higher pathogen pressure on terrestrial and marine ecosystems.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] In many ecosystems higher biodiversity could contribute to greater resilience to pests and diseases, as diversity in host traits and interactions can interrupt disease spread and reduce the severity of the outbreak.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] In coastal ecosystems genetic diversity within a species can further enhance its adaptive capacity by providing a range of traits that support populations to persist under changing temperature and precipitation regimes.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Furthermore, in terrestrial ecosystems higher biodiversity can promote mutualistic interactions (like pollination or mycorrhizal networks), which can enhance nutrient uptake and support overall productivity and resilience.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The other category of agricultural diversity is called interspecific diversity and refers to the number and types of different species.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Agricultural diversity can also be divided by whether it is 'planned' diversity or 'associated' diversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] This is a functional classification that we impose and not an intrinsic feature of life or diversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Associated biodiversity can be damaging or beneficial.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The beneficial associated biodiversity include for instance wild pollinators such as wild bees and syrphid flies that pollinate crops and natural enemies and antagonists to pests and pathogens.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Beneficial associated biodiversity occurs abundantly in crop fields and provide multiple ecosystem services such as pest control, nutrient cycling and pollination that support crop production.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Although about 80 percent of humans' food supply comes from just 20 kinds of plants, humans use at least 40,000 species.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Earth's surviving biodiversity provides resources for increasing the range of food and other products suitable for human use, although the present extinction rate shrinks that potential.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity's relevance to human health is becoming an international political issue, as scientific evidence builds on the global health implications of biodiversity loss.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Some of the health issues influenced by biodiversity include dietary health and nutrition security, infectious disease, medical science and medicinal resources, social and psychological health.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is also known to have an important role in reducing disaster risk, including rising sea levels.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] For example, wetland ecosystems along coastal communities serve as excellent water filtration systems, storage, and ultimately create a buffer region between the ocean and mainland neighborhoods in order to prevent water reaching these communities under climate change pressures or storm surges.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Other examples of diverse species or organisms are present around the world, offering their resourceful utilities to provide protection of human survival.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity provides critical support for drug discovery and the availability of medicinal resources.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Only a tiny fraction of wild species has been investigated for medical potential.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] This process of bioprospecting can increase biodiversity loss, as well as violating the laws of the communities and states from which the resources are taken.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] According to the Boston Consulting Group, in 2021, the economic value that biodiversity has on society comes down to four definable terms: regulation, culture, habitat, and provisioning.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] To sum these up in a relatively short manner, biodiversity helps maintain habitat and animal functions that provide considerable amounts of resources that benefit the economy.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity's economic resources are worth at around $150 trillion annually which is roughly twice the world's GDP.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The loss of biodiversity is actually harming the GDP of the world by costing an estimated $5 trillion annually.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Business supply chains rely heavily on ecosystems remaining relatively maintained and nurtured.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] A disruption to these supply chains would negatively impact many businesses that would end up costing them more than what they are gaining.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Philosophically it could be argued that biodiversity has intrinsic aesthetic and spiritual value to mankind *in and of itself*.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] This idea can be used as a counterweight to the notion that tropical forests and other ecological realms are only worthy of conservation because of the services they provide.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity also affords many non-material benefits including spiritual and aesthetic values, knowledge systems and education.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] A variety of objective means exist to empirically measure biodiversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Each measure relates to a particular use of the data, and is likely to be associated with the variety of genes.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is commonly measured in terms of taxonomic richness of a geographic area over a time interval.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] In order to calculate biodiversity, species evenness, species richness, and species diversity are to be obtained first.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] *Species evenness* is the relative number of individuals of each species in a given area.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] *Species richness* is the number of species present in a given area.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] *Species diversity* is the relationship between species evenness and species richness.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] There are many ways to measure biodiversity within a given ecosystem.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] However, the two most popular are Shannon-Weaver diversity index, commonly referred to as Shannon diversity index, and the other is Simpsons diversity index.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Although many scientists prefer to use Shannon's diversity index simply because it takes into account species richness.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Less than 1% of all species that have been described have been studied beyond noting their existence.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The vast majority of Earth's species are microbial.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Contemporary biodiversity physics is "firmly fixated on the visible [macroscopic] world".
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] For example, microbial life is metabolically and environmentally more diverse than multicellular life (see e.g., extremophile).
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] "On the tree of life, based on analyses of small-subunit ribosomal RNA, visible life consists of barely noticeable twigs.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The inverse relationship of size and population recurs higher on the evolutionary ladder—to a first approximation, all multicellular species on Earth are insects".
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Insect extinction rates are high—supporting the Holocene extinction hypothesis.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity naturally varies due to seasonal shifts.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Spring's arrival enhances biodiversity as numerous species breed and feed, while winter's onset temporarily reduces it as some insects perish and migrating animals leave.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Additionally, the seasonal fluctuation in plant and invertebrate populations influences biodiversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Barriers such as large rivers, seas, oceans, mountains and deserts encourage diversity by enabling independent evolution on either side of the barrier, via the process of allopatric speciation.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The term invasive species is applied to species that breach the natural barriers that would normally keep them constrained.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Without barriers, such species occupy new territory, often supplanting native species by occupying their niches, or by using resources that would normally sustain native species.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Species are increasingly being moved by humans (on purpose and accidentally).
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Some studies say that diverse ecosystems are more resilient and resist invasive plants and animals.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Many studies cite effects of invasive species on natives, but not extinctions.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Invasive species seem to increase local (alpha diversity) diversity, which decreases turnover of diversity (beta diversity).
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Overall gamma diversity may be lowered because species are going extinct because of other causes, but even some of the most insidious invaders (e.g.: Dutch elm disease, emerald ash borer, chestnut blight in North America) have not caused their host species to become extinct.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Extirpation, population decline and homogenization of regional biodiversity are much more common.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Human activities have frequently been the cause of invasive species circumventing their barriers, by introducing them for food and other purposes.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Human activities therefore allow species to migrate to new areas (and thus become invasive) occurred on time scales much shorter than historically have been required for a species to extend its range.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] At present, several countries have already imported so many exotic species, particularly agricultural and ornamental plants, that their indigenous fauna/flora may be outnumbered.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] For example, the introduction of kudzu from Southeast Asia to Canada and the United States has threatened biodiversity in certain areas.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Another example are pines, which have invaded forests, shrublands and grasslands in the southern hemisphere.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Endemic species can be threatened with extinction through the process of genetic pollution, i.e. uncontrolled hybridization, introgression and genetic swamping.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Genetic pollution leads to homogenization or replacement of local genomes as a result of either a numerical and/or fitness advantage of an introduced species.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Hybridization and introgression are side-effects of introduction and invasion.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] These phenomena can be especially detrimental to rare species that come into contact with more abundant ones.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The abundant species can interbreed with the rare species, swamping its gene pool.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] This problem is not always apparent from morphological (outward appearance) observations alone.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Some degree of gene flow is normal adaptation and not all gene and genotype constellations can be preserved.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] However, hybridization with or without introgression may, nevertheless, threaten a rare species' existence.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Conservation biology matured in the mid-20th century as ecologists, naturalists and other scientists began to research and address issues pertaining to global biodiversity declines.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] The conservation ethic advocates management of natural resources for the purpose of sustaining biodiversity in species, ecosystems, the evolutionary process and human culture and society.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Conservation biology is reforming around strategic plans to protect biodiversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Preserving global biodiversity is a priority in strategic conservation plans that are designed to engage public policy and concerns affecting local, regional and global scales of communities, ecosystems and cultures.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Action plans identify ways of sustaining human well-being, employing natural capital, macroeconomic policies including economic incentives, and ecosystem services.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] In the EU Directive 1999/22/EC zoos are described as having a role in the preservation of the biodiversity of wildlife animals by conducting research or participation in breeding programs.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Removal of exotic species will allow the species that they have negatively impacted to recover their ecological niches.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Exotic species that have become pests can be identified taxonomically (e.g., with Digital Automated Identification SYstem (DAISY), using the barcode of life).
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] Removal is practical only given large groups of individuals due to the economic cost.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p01] As sustainable populations of the remaining native species in an area become assured, "missing" species that are candidates for reintroduction can be identified using databases such as the *Encyclopedia of Life* and the Global Biodiversity Information Facility.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas, including forest reserves and biosphere reserves, serve many functions including for affording protection to wild animals and their habitat.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas have been set up all over the world with the specific aim of protecting and conserving plants and animals.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Some scientists have called on the global community to designate as protected areas of 30 percent of the planet by 2030, and 50 percent by 2050, in order to mitigate biodiversity loss from anthropogenic causes.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] The target of protecting 30% of the area of the planet by the year 2030 (30 by 30) was adopted by almost 200 countries in the 2022 United Nations Biodiversity Conference.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] At the moment of adoption (December 2022) 17% of land territory and 10% of ocean territory were protected.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] In a study published 4 September 2020 in Science Advances researchers mapped out regions that can help meet critical conservation and climate goals.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas safeguard nature and cultural resources and contribute to livelihoods, particularly at local level.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] There are over 238 563 designated protected areas worldwide, equivalent to 14.9 percent of the earth's land surface, varying in their extension, level of protection, and type of management (IUCN, 2018).
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] The benefits of protected areas extend beyond their immediate environment and time.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] In addition to conserving nature, protected areas are crucial for securing the long-term delivery of ecosystem services.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] They provide numerous benefits including the conservation of genetic resources for food and agriculture, the provision of medicine and health benefits, the provision of water, recreation and tourism, and for acting as a buffer against disaster.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Increasingly, there is acknowledgement of the wider socioeconomic values of these natural ecosystems and of the ecosystem services they can provide.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] A national park is a large natural or near natural area set aside to protect large-scale ecological processes, which also provide a foundation for environmentally and culturally compatible, spiritual, scientific, educational, recreational and visitor opportunities.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] These areas are selected by governments or private organizations to protect natural biodiversity along with its underlying ecological structure and supporting environmental processes, and to promote education and recreation.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), and its World Commission on Protected Areas (WCPA), has defined "National Park" as its Category II type of protected areas.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Wildlife sanctuaries are areas of either shelter for animals who are unable to live in the wild on their own, or they are temporary rehabilitation centers for wildlife to improve in their overall health and wellbeing.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Both of these serve as places in which biodiversity can be preserved rather than harmed.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] According to an article published in the National Park Service website, national parks aim their resources at maintaining animal and habitat integrity through conservation and preservation of their ecosystems.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] This along with educating the general public on wildlife functions, the aim for an increase in biodiversity is one of many goals trying to be focused on through national parks.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Forest protected areas are a subset of all protected areas in which a significant portion of the area is forest.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] This may be the whole or only a part of the protected area.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Globally, 18 percent of the world's forest area, or more than 700 million hectares, fall within legally established protected areas such as national parks, conservation areas and game reserves.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] There is an estimated 726 million ha of forest in protected areas worldwide.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Of the six major world regions, South America has the highest share of forests in protected areas, 31 percent.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] The forests play a vital role in harboring more than 45,000 floral and 81,000 faunal species of which 5150 floral and 1837 faunal species are endemic.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] In addition, there are 60,065 different tree species in the world.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Plant and animal species confined to a specific geographical area are called endemic species.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] In forest reserves, rights to activities like hunting and grazing are sometimes given to communities living on the fringes of the forest, who sustain their livelihood partially or wholly from forest resources or products.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Approximately 50 million hectares (or 24%) of European forest land is protected for biodiversity and landscape protection.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Forests allocated for soil, water, and other ecosystem services encompass around 72 million hectares (32% of European forest area).
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] It stated that "the state of nature has deteriorated at an unprecedented and accelerating rate".
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] To fix the problem, humanity will need a transformative change, including sustainable agriculture, reductions in consumption and waste, fishing quotas and collaborative water management.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] The concept of nature-positive is playing a role in mainstreaming the goals of the Global Biodiversity Framework (GBF) for biodiversity.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] The aim of mainstreaming is to embed biodiversity considerations into public and private practice to conserve and sustainably use biodiversity on global and local levels.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] The concept of nature-positive refers to the societal goal to halt and reverse biodiversity loss, measured from a baseline of 2020 levels, and to achieve full so-called "nature recovery" by 2050.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Citizen science, also known as public participation in scientific research, has been widely used in environmental sciences and is particularly popular in a biodiversity-related context.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] It has been used to enable scientists to involve the general public in biodiversity research, thereby enabling the scientists to collect data that they would otherwise not have been able to obtain.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Volunteer observers have made significant contributions to on-the-ground knowledge about biodiversity, and recent improvements in technology have helped increase the flow and quality of occurrences from citizen sources.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] A 2016 study published in Biological Conservation registers the massive contributions that citizen scientists already make to data mediated by the Global Biodiversity Information Facility (GBIF).
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Despite some limitations of the dataset-level analysis, it is clear that nearly half of all occurrence records shared through the GBIF network come from datasets with significant volunteer contributions.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Recording and sharing observations are enabled by several global-scale platforms, including iNaturalist and eBird.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Global agreements such as the Convention on Biological Diversity, give "sovereign national rights over biological resources" (not property).
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] The agreements commit countries to "conserve biodiversity", "develop resources for sustainability" and "share the benefits" resulting from their use.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Biodiverse countries that allow bioprospecting or collection of natural products, expect a share of the benefits rather than allowing the individual or institution that discovers/exploits the resource to capture them privately.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Bioprospecting can become a type of biopiracy when such principles are not respected.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Sovereignty principles can rely upon what is better known as Access and Benefit Sharing Agreements (ABAs).
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] The Convention on Biodiversity implies informed consent between the source country and the collector, to establish which resource will be used and for what and to settle on a fair agreement on benefit sharing.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] The agreement includes also recovering 30% of earth degraded ecosystems and increasing funding for biodiversity issues.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] In May 2020, the European Union published its Biodiversity Strategy for 2030.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] The biodiversity strategy is an essential part of the climate change mitigation strategy of the European Union.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] From the 25% of the European budget that will go to fight climate change, large part will go to restore biodiversity and nature based solutions.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Approximately half of the global GDP depend on nature.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] In Europe many parts of the economy that generate trillions of euros per year depend on nature.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] The benefits of Natura 2000 alone in Europe are €200 – €300 billion per year.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Uniform approval for use of biodiversity as a legal standard has not been achieved, however.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] Bosselman argues that biodiversity should not be used as a legal standard, claiming that the remaining areas of scientific uncertainty cause unacceptable administrative waste and increase litigation without promoting preservation goals.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] India passed the Biological Diversity Act in 2002 for the conservation of biological diversity in India.
[src:arkive/biodiversity-p02] The Act also provides mechanisms for equitable sharing of benefits from the use of traditional biological resources and knowledge.
[src:arkive/biological-classification] In biology, **taxonomy** (from Ancient Greek τάξις*(taxis)* 'arrangement' and -νομία*(-nomia)* 'method') is the scientific study of naming, defining (circumscribing) and classifying groups of biological organisms based on shared characteristics.
[src:arkive/biological-classification] Modern approaches prioritize common ancestry and evolutionary relationships.
[src:arkive/biological-classification] Organisms are grouped into taxa (singular: taxon), and these groups are given a taxonomic rank; groups of a given rank can be aggregated to form a more inclusive group of higher rank, thus creating a taxonomic hierarchy.
[src:arkive/biological-classification] The principal ranks in modern use are domain, kingdom, phylum (*division* is sometimes used in botany in place of *phylum*), class, order, family, genus, and species.
